,Recommended,290300,33246757,Posted: 4 July,all,SidAlpha,"https://youtu.be/15cJ4e2KQB0Rebel Galaxy is an amazing Open World game that takes clear inspirations from Freelancer and Firefly, to name but a few. With an impressive array of features and far more depth than I had anticipated, this game is an absolute gem of a find ond one that is well worth your money. Given the content involved, I would expect it to cost $30, not it's regular $20 price tag.However, the game does make use of a 2D flight plane as opposed to a 3D movement range, but that is a fairly minor complaint and doesn't hold the game back at all."
76561198065054287,Recommended,290300,18670974,"Posted: 24 October, 2015",all,Nyax,"If you're looking for a space pew pew lazorz game, just buy it. Right now. What are you waiting for? Stop reading these words and go buy it.You're still reading? Fine I'll put more words here that might mean things about stuff. Seriously, though, this game overdelivers its $20 at release date price (or whatever you can get it for on sale). There are plenty of other reviews speaking to what's great about this game, so I won't beat a dead horse. However, I would like to speak to some of the negative comments that I've seen.""Missions are repetitive."" - this is true, but that hasn't reduced my enjoyment of gameplay. Sure the missions are repetitive, but each encounter does have variations within it. There are at least 3 major variations with each mission: mission type, types of friendlies, types of enemies.There are escort missions (follow a friendly around at warp speed and defend them from attacking hostiles that pull you out of warm), defend missions (move into an engagement and prevent friendlies from being destroyed), destroy missions (fly in guns blazing until everything is on fire, including you), snatch and run / fight missions (fly into an area teeming with hostiles, grab some cargo, and gtfo), delivery missions (get some cargo and deliver it to another station, while being pulled out of warp multiple times from hostiles trying to take your cargo). There are also other types that I haven't done yet (pirate missions).The other aspect that changes missions are types of friendlies/enemies. Sometimes you're fighting multiple cruisers with minor fighter support, sometimes you're fighting a dreadnaught with tons of fighter support, sometimes you're fighting waves upon waves of fighters - and yes these do require different engagement tactics. Good luck charging into waves of mine layer / bomber fighters with a cruiser and winning.I also feel like I need to point out that repetitive side missions aren't a new thing. How many times have you collected herbs as a side quest in some other RPG?""2D space combat"" - When I read this before buying it, I wasn't sure how I would feel about it. After playing the game - I just don't care that it's not 3D. I don't feel like it being 3D would make it any more fun, especially with the ""broadside"" style gameplay (which I do enjoy). The 2D movement environment plus broadside style combat provides enough complexity without making it over-complex. You can still use tactics to use a smaller vessel to take down a larger one. I've used my quick cruiser to take down multiple dreadnaughts by getting behind them so that the only damage I'm taking is from their rear turrets and the occasional heat seeking missile, and they can't turn fast enough to broadside me. Plus with a fast vessel you have enough maneuverability to be able to zig-zag between your broadsides (shields don't depreciate as a whole - but each side is separate, for a total of 4 shields) to be able to keep your shields up, all while staying out of the main line of fire. Or you could just buy a huge ship, get ramming deflectors, AND RAMMING SPEED EVERYTHING TO DEATH. Twice.""Main Storyline is [insert words]"" I'm not sure why people are complaining about the main storyline. At the time of writing this I've had 26 hours in the game and still haven't finished it. Sure it's nothing especially fancy... but it is engaging, and seriously it's a $20 game. I'm not sure what you expect. I've played plenty of single player RPG-style games (ones that ONLY have a main storyline) that I've cleared in under 30 hours, and those were $50-60 at release.""Soundtrack something or other"" I also really enjoyed the soundtrack with it's Firefly vibe, however I would have to agree that it starts getting repetitive. I also have an easy solution. Turn off the music. Play your own if you really want music. Again, for a $20 game the soundtrack exceeds what I would expect.Final thoughts - the depth and enjoyability of the game overdelivers as a $20 price tag, making it a worthwhile purchase.  I would also like to see (and gladly pay for) some DLC/expansions to further increase the depth of the game (greater variety of missions, more ships, more weapons, more factions, expand main storyline, more musc, online co-op play)End transmission?"
76561198028325917,Recommended,290300,18634950,"Posted: 22 October, 2015",all,TamaSaga,"26 hours in and I'm basically in world 2.When I play this game, I keep thinking that this is what Freelancer should have been.  When I played Freelancer, I had a ""was that it?"" feeling.  Contrarily, Rebel Galaxy gives off a ""not JUST a space flight adventure simulator"" sort of vibe.Yay:- Ignore the story, earn money, buy really big ships.- Ability to join multiple guilds without needing to quit your current one- Broadside combat in a space sim is surprisingly fun.- Very responsive devs, check the bug reports part of the forum- Prices of commodities go up and down in response to world events and planetary type- Wide variety of missions.  Escort, Pickup, Delivery, Blockade Running, Head hunting...- No speed lanes, you want to get somewhere fast just point your nose and punch the warp.- Dynamic system.  In Wing Commander: Privateer, you could watch the news and respond accordingly to major events.  Is there a famine?  Bring food.  War?  Bring weapons.  Market glut, buy low.  This system is rarely found in these space trading games.  I don't think Freelancer had it.- Good voice acting- Intuitive game design- Aliens!- Varied Nebulas.  Including the classic ones like lightning nebulas that can shatter your shields in a single flash and dark nebulas where danger and mystery lurk within.- Scanner.  A nifty halo emits from your ship and lets you know of nearby enemies, allies, and items.Nay:- Broadside combat is rather easy.  Just manuever until your side is exposed, use precise targetting, and press a button.  The lead is automatically calculated for you.  The only thing you need to decide is how much time to charge the shot.- Fighters are so annoying since they can go to the 3rd dimension.  Plus the strike craft defense options are a bit lacking due to their extremely limited range.  You're left with relying on general-purpose turrets to pick off the pesky gnats one at a time.- No speed lanes.  Most of the time, I neglect to plot a proper course before warping so I end up going through like 3 asteroid fields, 2 debris fields, and 1 planet.  That's like hitting 6 red lights when you're trying to get somewhere.Meh:- No idle radio chatter- From what I've played so far, you pass lots of planets but there is no planetary landing.  You always stop at a station in orbit.  I'm guessing the idea is that space ships should stay in space where they're designed to work."
,Recommended,290300,18605955,"Posted: 21 October, 2015",all,remaru,"TL;DRIt's fun, simple, and (10/21/15) on sale. Go ahead, buy it. It's not Elite, it's not X3TC, it's not Eve and that's ok. Single player, good Xbox controller controls, lots of things to shoot at.Good:Lots of space, without tons of jumpgates/load screensSimple controls that work well with a Xbox controllerStory is interesting enough to kill time with, nothing award winning, but it's there, you're there, might as wellWhen upgrading a ship all of your old equipment just carries over, no having to rebuild your shipBad:Music gets real old, real fast. It sounds great at first, but hearing the same song over and over again for hours gets annoying.Not alot of loadout choices. There are more ships than weapons (not really, but close)Best of the best of everything is really expensive and doesn't do that much more than the basic equipmentCan only have 1 ship"
,Recommended,290300,19658962,"Posted: 12 December, 2015",all,Megakoresh,"Rebel Galaxy is a cautios recommendation. For 20€ it's a good game. It has some major flaws, but I would still call it a good game at the end of the day. I'll try this review in a different format, because this is a game that could have been a hidden gem of the year if developers had a little different focus. So:What this game should have hadFirst and absolutely foremost: Context. That was SUCH a huge miss. The game provides no context for anything outside of the main quest.Missions and systems have zero context. They are condensed to a marker on the map. No characters to talk to, no multiple ways to complete missions, no multi-staged missions, no consequences. Even faction missions have absolutely no context.Every trader is one of two possible models, they all have exactly the same lines, regardless of where and how you meet them.All mercenaries are 5 characters that inexplicably appear in every system on random stations and can't be interacted with beyond ""Hey, what ship you fly?"", ""What's your skills?"" and ""You are hired"".Really really huge miss, because the mechanics of this game are very simplistic and can not justify the complete absence of context.Fast travel. 90% of the gameplay time is wasted on the annoying warp mechanic.There's no fast travel and you have to go between stations very often. During warp you have to manually aim your ship and it won't exit out of warp unless you aim it dead on point, so you can't just alt-tab and check email. You have to stare at the screen.You get pulled out of warp on every tiny object to the side of your path. And there are a LOT of meaningless tiny objects in this game.You can not engage warp again until after you are cleared from any mass, and it takes a while to accelerate enough to start warping again so travelling turns into an incredibly boring and frustrating experience that you have to endure a lot.What this game should have ditched to get the aboveScale. The game is absolutely unnecessarily large.You have something like 12 systems (don't remember exact number), each has about as many space stations. To travel through the whole map and visit every station once would require a full day of gameplay. And EACH station has like 6 contract missions, all of which are done with one of 3 main templates (fetch quest, elimination and escort), and might as well be MMORPG repeating quests.All of the stations are exactly the same. They vary only in what merc sits inside and the prices they offer on goods. The bartenders have the same dialogue, there are no interesting quests to pick up, no characters to talk to. Hell - even weapons and ships they offer are the same. Only faction stations offer different equipment.All in all it's a typical quantity over quality issue. The game could have been 10 times smaller (not exaggerating, I actually think that would be the proper reduction), but if it had actually interesting quests with dialogue, context and variety to offer it would have been much better for it.Economy. It's just uninteresting and not worth your time.The entire economy in the game could be thrown out and it wouldn't be missed. It's your basic buy low sell high economy, except fetching goods in this game, as I've explained, is tiresome and frustrating, and there's no market manipulation you can perform.The money you get out of it is rather small, overall I just don't think there's any reason to try and make money with it.It's not an MMO. There's no infinite high end equipment and clans and raids you can spend that dosh on. You can buy one of the overpriced heavy dreadnaughts, but... why? They aren't fun to use and what would you use it for anyway? Fetching more goods? It's just pointless and wasted resources IMO.Equipment could have been made into upgradable loot drops - you can't buy gear, but you can upgrade it with dosh and missions. That would have made the game far more engaging too, bring some variety in. As it stands, once I bought a full combo of guns, I just used the same set of equipment throughout the entire game, upgrading it.So as you can see there are some big issues. So what's good?What's good?Combat. It's very similar to Assassin's Creed Black Flag naval combat, just in Space. It's very cinematic, albiet not exactly difficult. It's by no means a sim, it's absolutely unrealistic and very arcady, but that doesn't really matter. It's fun. That's the main thing.Combat's difficulty comes from how the game is balanced - it is very binary. You are either not having any problems whatsoever, or you are dead. Ship's HP is very small. Your shields and armour are what protect you.The main skill in this game is to turn your ship all the time to let the shields on another side regenerate. You must never let enemies surround you and you must maneuvre such that you take as little continuous fire as possible, while spreading the damage over all your shields.This is also a reason why you never want to fly a dreadnaught. Small ship that you can turn to spread damage across all your 4 shields and platings is more survivable than large ship which is gonna take all the damage to one side.Sountrack - amazing rock and country music, with cinematic arcade combat in a spectacle of lazers and explosions. What more could you ask for?Graphics - the game looks good obviously.Polish - the game runs well and never crashed or bugged out on me.Aliens - they look and sound cool. I think the alien languages aren't necessary, but the looks and voice modifiers are cool.Progression - there's a variety of cool ships on display and all except dreadnaughts are quite fun to use. Also there is a large variety of guns you can install, each with a specific strength and weakness. You can take control of any gun directly, through in my experience turrets are always better controlled by the AI. Usually you are better off controlling broadsides and maneuvering the ship for the most advantageous angle.Atmosphere. The game's light-hearted atmosphere with a few funny lines of text here and there blend well with combat and music.So in the end I think the game is quite good for what it is. I just think it would have been a hell of a lot better had the developers more clearly understood it's strengths and weaknesses. A cautious recommendation, but a recommendation nonetheless."
76561198014874377,Not Recommended,290300,29661147,Posted: 2 February,all,AMG,"Pros:- Space dogfighting. The broadside cannon system is interesting, and keeping the fighting mostly in 2D solves a lot of the problems associated with this idea. It's enjoyable for a while.- Good story. Interesting enough for the length of the game.- Great soundtrack - look for the playlist on Spotify. I love how when combat happens the music gets more aggressive.Cons:- So damn grindy. In between story missions you'll need to buy improvements on your ship. Have fun doing tons of redundant quests or flying everywhere trying to trade for money.- Speaking of trade, it's largely a waste of time. While you can certainly make money flying around and taking advantage of market conditions, there's never enough stock of anything to make large amounts of money without making the rounds of every solar system. Towards  the end of the game trade is outright worthless as any cargo drop from a ship is worth more than an entire shipload of cargo that you purchased.- Mining is worthless unless you get lucky, don't bother.I would have loved this game if there was more trade\mining options to improve your ship so that I could try different weapons configurations, but I never had enough cash, and the grind became too much for me so I just ended the game.I'm happy I played it if for no other reason than the soundtrack is so outstanding and I was introduced to a whole genre of music I've never listened to. But the game play is just meh."
76561198108269527,Recommended,290300,19324894,"Posted: 27 November, 2015",all,quantum_jak,"After years and years of personally wishing for new space sims, Starpoint Gemini 2, Elite Dangerous and this game all came out within a year's time.Of the three games, this one has the glossiest presentation and best-presented story line. This is like Starpoint Gemini 2 in that the perspective is third person because you are controlling capital-ship sized vessels. There are many jobs and sidequests in addition to the story line and different factions that you can side with or against.Is this a hardcore sim? Absolutely not, but it is fun and combat heavy. Apparently in this galaxy there are hordes of pirates and alien raiders to do battle with...Recommended if you like flying around the galaxy and lots of explosions."
,Recommended,290300,23949575,"Posted: 30 June, 2016",all,Viper123_SWE,"Did you ever watchFireflyand think""Hey, it would be really cool with a game where I can be a space cowboy""?If no, that means you're either in the wrong place or you haven't watched Firefly. Go do that now.If yes, then look no further!Rebel Galaxyis a singleplayer open-world spaceship RPG set in distant future.As the player, you receive a message from your old aunt Juno asking you to travel to the frontier. Riddled with piracy, military conflicts, intrigues and other mysteries your arrival marks the beginning of a long journey.Aside from the story you can choose to undertake thousands (if not more) of different sidejobs, it can be anything from an escort mission to the elimination of a key pirate leader hiding in a asteroid field.Freedom is key and the player has many choices available to them, each granting you different perks but also changing the way the rest of the galaxy sees you.A player who help traders and merchants during distress calls or who actively pursue pirate fleets will be seen as friendly by the Confederate militia while a player who smuggles contraband, ambush militia patrols and disrupt authorities will be seen as a friend by the pirates.In Rebel Galaxy the systems you fly in feel very much alive, stopping at a station just to view the newsboard inside the bar is a good idea as it will provide you with all kinds of information regarding politics, bounties or good trading opportunities.Planets can go to war with eachother, raising the demand for military equipment which in turn allows you to profit from it. If you want the conflict to escalate you can destroy any treaty vessels which attempt to broke peace.NewsboardOr maybe you're more of a honest businessman? If so tech booms and market gluts will be your best friends, lowering the value of goods at certain stations so you can buy them en masse only to sell them off at a fringe world for a hefty sum of credits.MarketIf that doesn't sound like your type of gig you can always become a freelancing bountyhunter or mercenary, tracking down pirate lords or escorting merchants through rough space.The choice is yours.GameplayGameplay-wise Rebel Galaxy is pretty straightforward, with easy-to-understand mechanics, helpful tutorial prompts and simple controls.CombatIn Rebel Galaxy the combat relies on three things: turrets, broadside ports and secondary ports.When not controlled by the player, turrets will act independently and target any hostile craft within the range or specific craft (you can choose).Broadsides are your main weapons and are used to obliterate enemy capital ships, broadsides can be anything from lasers to cannons.Finally, secondary ports are used for equipping fixed weapons and launchers such as flak guns, dumbfire missile launchers or mine catapults.Overall it's a very straightforward system even though it does get a bit repetitive after a certain point.Controls & UIThe controls for Rebel Galaxy are simple and easy to understand, the player has access to full control mapping.As for the UI, it's very clean and elegant. It shows exactly what you need without cluttering up the screen.UIAll in all Rebel Galaxy is a fun game. While it might suffer from being repetitive at a certain point it's stilla solid game which I highly recommend.Also, the soundtrack is amazing. Look it up.Fly safe."
