76561197974073331,Not Recommended,290300,18867551,"Posted: 3 November, 2015",all,Punisher_1,"I decided to change my review of this game to offer up points of why the game falls short. I'll summarize this as much as possible. If you want a very short review it is posted below.The super short review :6 out of 10 ( Good for fist timers and the younger gaming crowd )Anyone expecting a game with depth in story line and ship functionality will be disappointed. The story line is predictable, the benefits are minimal, everyone wins gaming.Would I play this game again? No, probably not unless the developer added many more features and vastly improved the game AI.The good:Overall a good looking game.Runs well, smooth.No crashes.Great sound track.Multiple paths to follow to end game ( Merchant, Pirate, Combat, Miner )The Bad:You ""fly"" on a single plane and cannot go up or down. While this is a space game I feel ike I am driving a tank or playing a FPS.The weapons systems on your ship shoot through your ship most of the time.It is a race to get Mark 5 / 6 items, you could do without but then you may have a harder times with the game.You simply follow a simple path to the end game.There is never a bounty placed on your head for the waves of AI you slaughter, your participation is not recognized in this game at all, this includes news stories.Between Story line missions upgrading your ship is essential to completing the next mission you will not know this until you jump in and have a WTF moment.There is no communication between stations for commodities ( minerals and goods ) thus what you buy for in one place might not be worth anything in another or one system over it is double in price.You will never know unless you go there.Ships and ship components are at 100% trade in and up value.  Thus switching out weapon systems is never a loss nor is it better from one place to another.The AI never recognizes you. Sure while you can slaughter pirates whole sale in the hundreds, save countless traders or conduct crippling raids against the AI at no point does the dialog or your player presence change anything in the game. It is one dimensional.There are always more AI, Going to a pirate faction station and eliminating everything in sight does nothing. The stations cannot be destroyed so eradicating a system of pirate activity is impossible.Random encounters with AI fleets are pointless. Unless there is a bounty loot drops will not even pay for your spent missiles or damage you may take. Best to just avoid them.The face you see of the AI are all the same. Pirates will taunt you and well this is the 100th time you killed that same pirate. Aliens all look the same also. Even some side characters look just like the random pirates as well as the Militia.The lines for the AI or NPCs are the same and repetitive.Trell the AI the story line revolves around makes some minor upgrade to your ship. These are nothing amazing just some sensor and defensive bumps. The only time you interact with Trell is when she wants something ( typical woman ) For an AI with vast knowledge you would think she would tell you how to boost your weapon performance or make some great weapon system or a new type of ship.... nope.I came here to save Criminal Aunt Juno. However the dialogue with here does nothing to tell me why it would be worth it. No back story to tell me why I'd risk my♥♥♥♥♥to save this woman from the crap she got herself into.Random AI gotcha moments, taking on a merchant mission with a low threat level was not really low at all. This was a game breaking moment for me because it made no sense what so ever. Enemy ships appear out of nowhere, surround your ship and disable it thus killing your mobility. This continually happens while fleets ( from fighters to dreadnaughts ) of AI pop up randomly. To sum it up the game mechanics cheat. You can attempt to run or if you have the right ship component ( so I am told ) nullify the effects of the disabling missiles.The end game moments are really nothing special. I never got attached to Trell, she did nothing but get me into trouble, heck her upgrades were minimal at best. The was no big glorious end game movie clip or anything special for saving the galaxy from a deadly invasion. After all this Juno buys you a drink and that is the game.The end game:I wanted to finish up achieving the end game in the most ""advanced"" combat ship with a decent fitting. There was a level of satisfaction at that point because annihilating even a super dreadnaught AI at the end was easy.  Completed with mark 5 / 6 equipped Black Gate Dreadnaught 54,000,000 credits, 1498 enemy ships destroyed. This tacked on another 5 hours of game play before I took on the end game mission. The threat level went from Very High to Low.Wasted time, I spent a couple of hours sorting out the AI ""cheat issue"" with the Merchant mission before walking away from the missions. Ironically the combat missions were less dangerous. Exploration, mining and other activities burned up a few hours also. So in 20 to 24 hours you can complete this game with a solid kitted out ship."
