76561198005551488,Recommended,290300,24720221,"Posted: 4 August, 2016",all,Nubtard,"Imagine you're playing Assassin's Creed IV: Black Flag.  Now, imagine that instead of being stuck with that one, tiny, but somehow infinitely upgradable little ship, you can actually buy new ships as your fortunes improve.  Now, imagine you're in space.  Finally, imagine you don't have to get out of the ship to follow some British ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ around the island for 20 minutes in an area that is suddenly, inexplicably teeming with soldiers.I think I got sidetracked.  Anyway.  This is an excellent quasi-3D ship combat game.  Not a full 3D sim like Freelancer... all player-piloted ships, and those of similar size, seem to occupy the same plane of space.  Rolls, climbs, and dives are not valid maneuvers.  Shields go fore, aft, port, starboard, with no concern for doral or ventral.  Despite this, you don't feel particularly limited in your play.  It's just streamlining something that can overly complicate some other games.There is some downside.  There isn't a lot of variety to your available weaponry.  The targeting AI that controls your turrets most of the time is kinda stupid, and works in exclusive terms, rather that allowing prioritization.  There are, inevitably, escort missions, some of which you will lose for no good reason.  The in-game economy is a little capricious, which makes moving goods profitably as a trader a bit of a long game.  But I still find it enjoyable to spend a few hours making pretty explosions in space, set to a soundtrack that you might find playing in Jim Raynor's house back on Mar Sara- forgettable, upbeat, twangy rock."
76561197997555049,Recommended,290300,18816624,"Posted: 1 November, 2015",all,khemeher,"Two dudes got together, drank some energy drinks, and rocked out to Clutch while storyboarding a game.   They needed some fast cash to get their Chevy Nova off the cinder blocks, and had to do it both cheap & good.  They took the basic engine from Torchlight, used it to make a galaxy, and replaced people with spaceships.  They set it to motion with steel guitars, particle effects, and lots of badass.  Rebel Galaxy was born.Do you want to be a badass outlaw space trucker?  Can you deal with not being able to go up & down, an do barrel rolls in exchange for easy to use controls & fun combat?  Can you tell your OCD tendencies to STFU & just enjoy the content?  Most importantly, do you want to be a badass outlaw space trucker?Rebel Galaxy:  Malt liquor & unfiltered cigarettes not included."
