,Recommended,290300,18833598,"Posted: 2 November, 2015",all,Tman,"I finished the game, and it's time to write a love letter to Travis and Erich and all the people they contracted out for ship modeling / designs / voiceovers, etc.THANK YOU.From the bottom of my brown coat pocket, this is a game that immediately put me in what I could only imagine before ... something resembling the Firefly universe. I think you hit the absolutely sweet spot of fun / progression / story and artwork. I sometimes lost myself flying around, you made it really feel like I was out in outer-space, with the wide variety of planets / nebulas / junk fields / ice fields / asteroid fields, what have you. The sheer number of stations and objects you would run into while out in the cold really made it feel great.The care & thought you put into the simplified UI design was nothing short of brilliant. Simple & elegant.  I thought you had thought of everything and once when flying, my UI popped up and said ""It's been a while since you saved, you should dock at a station to save your game"" or something - then I knew you HAD thought of everything.The story was engaging, and the missions were enough of a large variety. Trade missions, assasination, protection, dead drops, the game really gives you a lot of options. So many cartels to see which one's you'll join / fight. The emergent game play - the distress signals (and ability to trade with the merchants was again a wise design choice as it reinforces saving their butts ;-), the un-identified signals, getting popped out in a junk or ice field, you made what should be a very empty space interesting while travelling around.For two guys and a small army of outside contractors / agents that you employed, this game rocks. I'm so glad that you decided to make this game.THANK YOU!!"
76561197963985477,Recommended,290300,29858621,Posted: 11 February,all,LaBrAt,"Having now played 60 hours into my first Rebel Galaxy playthrough, I feel i can give this game a solid review.Pros:- Awesome graphics (on max settings) that somehow find the right balance between cartoon-ish and realistic.- The ships are very customizable and they all look amazing, with pros and cons to each of them.- Custom music for any area of the game. (if you want to have shopping mall music in your space stations more power to you)- Simple yet effective combat system that relies heavily on shield management and ship positioning. (unless you want to repair at every station you dock at)- Accessible trading system. (buy when red, sell when green)- Good replayability due to the procedurally generated star systems.Cons:- WARP INHIBITED BY STELLAR MASS (this will be burned into your psyche) Literally everything kicks your ship out of warp once you are within 3.0 sm (solar mile??) of it. At least give me the option to smash my ship into an asteroid at warp if i'm that dumb.. this would be equivalent to getting demounted in an MMO every time you were within a few meters of a large rock or a tree... or another player.- While vast, the galaxy, and the solar systems feel lifeless. You will realize very quickly that you are playing a single player game in the cold loneliness of space.- Mining, is borderline pointless once you're at the point in the game where a single upgrade is well over $1,000,000. This is because the average mining drop is either obtanium or meteoric diamonds which sell for $1,000~, and $20,000~ respectively.- I found the default music to be irritating after listening to it for over 5 hours, though some people like it, at least there is the option to play without music or use your own.- The combat is mostly automated and based on whether your ship is stronger than the other one or not... not much outmaneuvering is possible in Rebel Galaxy, so you don't get rewarded for being a better pilot than your opponent.. that and the enemy AI is pretty terrible.- The economy and commerce of the game is completely random, so it makes trading at times very frustrating. Also, some comodoties becomes obsolete due to the limited storage space you have because of how little they sell for. There is also no way to sort or filter the viewing of the comodoties at stations, which you'd think would just be common sense. Any game in this day and age that has an auction house type system has the ability to sort and filter it. What i found to be the best way of making money was to just amass a ton of expensive comodoties and fly around the galaxy and rescue merchants. After resucing them, they will buy your stuff for the max market value, and you also get the cargo of whatever ship they were under fire from.- The story is very simplistic with some unique enemies generated from the missions, but overall it lacks any sort of emotional attachment to the characters or development of said characters. I will say however thatThe final mission with Trell's goodbye left me a bit dissatisfied, not sad mind you, just annoyed that there was no CGI end sequence like there was at the start of the game. Or even mid-game when she was telling you about how countless past civilizations used her for war etc. Would it have broken the budget to make a cutscene like that while she's explaining her origins? Probably.Overall, the game was fun to play, and advance with the new ships that i upgraded to, but i'm skeptical that i'll be coming back for round 2 anytime soon. Maybe if the weapons were more varied or the trading and economy was more flushed out the game would feel warmer and more dynamic, but i guess this is what you get for a budget title.Rating - 7/10"
