76561198052982921,Recommended,290300,34005845,Posted: 3 August,all,Daikataro,"Welp, a game that got me busy for so long, deserves a long review in turn, so here goes:As far as visuals go, the game does quite well for itself, specially considering it's not a AAA game. Developers managed to convey the emptiness of space, without making it a dull place with nothing to see. Plenty of asteroid belts, abandoned loot and friend and foe alike to encounter, ships look swell and enemies are threatening.Gameplay wise, if you like what you do in the first hour, then by all means keep going, if not, refund, because game will be basically more of the same. Main story line, and like 85% side quests fit the ""kill X"" or ""fetch"" style of quest, with a few escort missions in between. Not saying by any means they weren't entertaining, they were, but more variety would've been very welcome.As far as storyline goes, it is both sensate and a safe bet, without being too ambitious. A gadget lost to ages found and recovered, and a struggle with those who seek to possess it; entertaining enough to get you thru the game, yet without any ramifications or input in the matter, a classical storytelling.Factions and the such, honestly, near useless. If you♥♥♥♥♥♥someone off they're going to attack you on sight, and if you're pals with someone, they won't... that's it really. At least for me, it seemed pointless to befriend the militia anywhere past neutral so I wouldn't have to fight them as well, they don't help you, unlock adittional missions or anything. Guilds do give out certain benefits like extra ships and gizmos, but other than that, it's pretty pointless to try and be pals with anyone.As for trade, despite developers claiming otherwise, it is currently, almost entirely unused potential. It is absolutely POINTLESS to invest in a hidden caché for contraband, as the prices for such items fluctuate the low to mid ranges, and you can make the same or more credits with legal items. I never once felt inclined to buy contraband items, because the risk was not worth the money, when it could have been used as such a pivotal point of the game: risk dealing on illegal goods, for a hefty return on your investment. Even on legal stuff, devs promise it goes beyond ""buy cheap and sell expensive"" but in practice, it's exactly that. Events are pretty unimportant, and sometimes a station offering a good ""on surplus"" will sell more expensive than a normal, no event station.As for alternative gameplay styles, some people claim to be doing pretty good for themselves as miners or traders; I honestly did not make 1/100 of what I did as a mercenary, via mining or trading, at least when factoring the time invested. In the time it took me to farm enough meteoric diamonds to make half a million, I could have hopped across the system and complete 3 relief missions for thrice that amount.And finally, replayability, this is where the game loses a lot of shine. You can keep playing past the final mission, but have little incentive to do so. There is no New Game+ mode, no unlocked specials and honestly, once you buy a Dreadnaught class ship, you can literally dive head first into a cluster of enemies, and let the auto-turrets do the picking, all challenge is removed. It would be nice to face new threats that actually carried a risk, not just a ""pew pew die"" gameplay style.So, is the game worth it? Absolutely, even at full price. Would I recommend it? No doubt, but like I said, make sure you enjoy the mechanics and if you don't, refund, it doesn't get any different for the rest of the game. Does it need work? Very much, both for alternative gamestyles and replayability. Would I purchase DLC? Bring it on!"
