76561198035400192,Recommended,290300,28502546,"Posted: 20 December, 2016",all,gallagherrealmsforth,"I am enjoying this game immensely.  The capitol ship combat is a lot of fun and a nice change from the fighter craft games that I am mostly familiar with.  The broadside combat combined with AI turrets makes for an easy to learn and very fun experience.The only thing I am not sure about is the lack of three dimensional flying, but that only seems to make things easier.  I find that when I play I don't mind not having vertical maneuverability, so it doesn't seem to be that big a thing."
,Recommended,290300,18646461,"Posted: 23 October, 2015",all,Gamboh,"This is a review discussing specific points about the game as a comparison for veterans of the genre.An excellent free roaming space game. Very much a Freelancer for the new generation, featuring Capital class vessels!THIS GAME IS JUST FINE WITH A KEYBOARD AND MOUSE, DONT LET OTHER REVIEWERS TURN YOU OFF OF IT BECAUSE YOU DONT HAVE A GAMEPAD!So, in Rebel Galaxy,the value of ALL of the parts you buy for your ship is fully refundable.Including ship chassis. You're free to experiment with new types of loadout at will. No charge for resale at all.There's a stat in the pause menu that shows yourNet Worth, including your ship and all of the parts you have on it, what's in your cargo hold, etc. It's a great way to do a single-player space exploration game.People complain a LOT about warping taking too long, but I don't find it a problem at all. You can get upgrades to your warp drive that increase the speed dramatically. As for hitting asteroid belts during a warp, you can and SHOULD watch for oncoming nebulae and asteroid fields. You can literally see them coming from a million miles away, and just steer out of the way. Snake around space for a better paralax view, so you can tell whether you're coming up on something big.Combat is on a 2d plane for capital class vessels, and a 3d plane for fighters and bombers.So, your turrets can hit stuff above and below you depending on their placement, and your side-guns are primarily for hitting the bigger stuff.There is a surprisingly large number of ships in the game, I'd put my currently seen number at about 20. Each faction has their own set of ships on offer. I particularly like the trade faction's GIGANTIC verticall wall of shipping containers, bristling with turrets and cannons.When considering your loadout, you spend a lot of time trying to strike a good balance between equipping anti-fighter, anti-cap, anti-shield, or anti-armor. Each turret and cannon has it's own set of attributes, and the jack-of-all-trades stuff is lacking a little in the numbers department. Over all, weapons feel good and balanced between types, with a slight leaning toward Mining Lasers at the start. I found them good for the first system, and switched out to specialized guns later.The cowboy music aesthetic is nice, very firefly. I ended up turning it off after a few hours of hearing the same four or five tracks, and loaded up a playlist with all the Star Wars music from the original trilogy. Definitely a good choice.Bountiesare very easy to get in to. You can find them at random when flying about by using your PULSE scanner, and waiting for the ""Bounty Detected!"" notice, then flying to the nearest enemy group. You can get map icons and waypoints to them by paying a small fee to bartenders at any station.While flying about, you'll come across lots of other stuff too.Message terminalsthat you can hack with a simple timed button-puzzle put waypoints on your map marking weapons caches and asteroid belts uncommonly rich in minerals. You can finddistress beacons, traders or military who are fighting a losing battle and pay you VERY well to save them! You can also find""Pirate Lords""floating around out there. They are elusive and unusually powerful enemies with huge bounties on them.Missionsare the same old cookie cutter, go here, kill stuff, gather items, come back. But! You can take three at a time, and bang them out really quick. Every station has missions, you can see the relative difficulty of each one as a color-coded mission title, green being easy, red being hard. It's actually quite accurate so far, hard missions definitely require some interesting strategies.The missions pay out as SOON as you complete the objective,so if it's just a kill order, you don't need to return for the reward. Super handy!Some of the later trade-faction missions are super lucrative, but require you to actually go find minerals on your own time. I got a mission to gather Pure Water that took me an hour or so due to NONE of the local stations having any, but that could be why I got the mission in the first place! I ended up mining out a few ice asteroids for the loot, and the reward was over $300,000.Tradeitself in the game is very simple. Go to station, find merchandise that is selling low, travel around until you find a place to sell high. Each station you visit will book the sale price of each item FOR YOU, and then map them on a really clever line graph showing maximum price, minimum price, and the average price. This means you can do everything at a glance, and don't need to worry about note keeping on paper.Cargo upgrades are pretty cheap, so most any ship can do some hauling. Obviously, gigantic hauling ships do have a lot more to offer that way though.Some ships concentrate much more heavily on rotating turrets, too.So if you don't like the whole ""Broadside"" dynamic, you really don't have to do it at all.I had a little cruiser with 7 turret slots and only 3 side guns, it was just perfect! The downside to a turret-ship is primarily cost. Turrets cost as much as the entire battery of your broadside guns. They lack a little in pure DPS as well, but you can easily make up for it with proper tactical positioning. Broadsiding is hard to line up against faster enemies, and makes you extremely vulerable to flanking by other enemy ships. It does have a pretty devestating hit if you nail another ship with the whole volley, though!You can blast fighters to smithereens with a well-placed cannon volley, too. That's a little tough, but super satisfying.Over all, I rate this game very highly. Each of it's features feel polished to a mirror sheen. It's very, VERY well thought out, and plays like a dream. I've run the gamut of space-freedom games from EVE to Freelancer to EV-Nova, and I feel like this game is a shining star in the genre!"
,Recommended,290300,18707045,"Posted: 26 October, 2015",all,[Tech] Knoar,"Think Elite Dangerous, but with naval combat and a good story.The naval-style combat deters a lot of people, but it actually works quite nicely with the single-plane orbit everything has in every solar system.  That means you can't fly up or down, only left or right.  However, smaller fighter planes and asteroids can fly beneath or above you, requiring your ship's turret placements to be more strategic.You can trade, mine, steal, join factions, make factions hate you, help people in distress, escort ships, fight every time, flee every time (depending on ship speed).  You can play as good, neutral, or evil, or jump around and do whatever pays the most.The game allows you to easily put your own music into it.You can resell every ship or item for 100% retail value.  This means you can test out ships, weapons, defenses, etc. without fear of wasting money.  This is a nice way of getting around the fact that you can only own one ship at a time.I think this game is definitely worth the price.  As of writing this I have played 32 hours.  I'm not done with the main story line, and I don't think I will be for a while.  There is too much money to be made, and too many ships and ship upgrades to buy."
,Recommended,290300,33090707,Posted: 1 July,all,Allexio,"A surprisingly solid game with hours of entertainment.+ EXCELLENT economic system: buy stuff from one system to sell it to another -think stock trading, but slightly simpler.- Could use some polish. Often, finding the best spot to sell your loot is a pain when a simple extra piece of interface would've solved this issue.+ Good combat mechanics: think Assassin's creed black flag with a bit more complexity (but still the same action fun)+ Can't really fault it, it's the fun and fast paced black flag combat with some much better ship customisation which drastically changes the way you fight, allowing for more playstyles and ultimately more combat approach opportunities.+ Good practical ship customisation, plenty of ugprades, weapons, components to choose from.- Bad visual ship customisation (literally nothing here)+ Good world interaction and dynamism. (things that happen in the world affect you, the stations around you, etc. and there's always something happening)+ Good soundtrack but...- Very few tracks, becomes bery repetitive with time, however...+ The game lets you swap around your own tracks instead of game tracks for exploration, combat, menu, etc.- unlockables are badly tiered and not paced properly.- So far the story is kinda meh.+ Not that it matters because this is above all a space exploration and fighting game.+ A few factions that do things in the world and interact solidly with each other but...- There are too few, and they lack proper lore and atmosphere. Feels like they pulled out a name out of a name generator and that was it. So far, no faction loyalty quests.- Side Quests are repetitive and boring. Think Skyrim with a slightly bigger range.All in all, this game is easily a 7.5/10, even an 8 if you're into more than just the combat and are willing to spend a little time trading.If you see this game for less than £5 or 10$, buy it, it is definitely worth every penny of that."
