76561197995239792,Recommended,290300,32995102,Posted: 29 June,all,SlingBlade,This is a very simple but fun game. On the surface it is simply an arcade ship simulator on a mixed 2D/3D plane. However there is a deeper portion to the game for those that want to look for it. An interesting yet unobtrusive story serves as the impetus for exploring a galaxy populated by interesting characters from a multitude of species with their own agendas and factions as you find your way amongst the stars.Fans of the game Freelancer will feel right at home in Rebel Galaxy and find many of the same mechanics apply here. You can take on numerous roles to suit your gameplay with an array of different ships and classes of them to suit different playstyles. Everything from nimble corvettes to hulking dreadnoughts and lumbering transports are available to the player who has the cash to procure and outfit them.The only real issue is that there are a lot of minor controls that are poorly explained and require some player exploration to discern exactly how certain mechanics work. Beyond that the game is quite fun and engaging with a simplicity that means it can easily be picked up for a brief stint and set down again without any disruption.
76561197999908506,Recommended,290300,24902512,"Posted: 13 August, 2016",all,tsandl,"If this was being marketed as some $50 triple-A title, it would be disappointing, but as they say in the ad, it's 20 friggin' dollars (and that's when it's not on sale). Rebel Galaxy is a very simple game, and that is its strength and its weakness. If you're looking for a game with a deep story, complex controls, or a fully realized universe with a vibrant dynamic economy, then this ain't it.  Rebel Galaxy is just a fun way to pass the time. It's a nice looking space game with simple controls and a good cowboy rock soundtrack. Incidentally, if you don't like the soundtrack, or you just want a little more variety there is a way to replace or add to the playlist in the game's launcher. I like that it lets you add different folders for different parts of the game. You want honky-tonk piano in the stations, smooth jazz while exploring and speed metal during combat? You can do that.The game is easy to learn and easy to play so long as you understand that running is often a better option than fighting. A fast ship lets you choose your battles and outrun those nasty pirate ambushes that some players seem to have trouble with. It's also a fun way to play. I especially enjoyed the dead drop missions in which I warped into the middle of an enemy formation, grabbed the loot, and hightailed it out of there before they could say, ""Prepare to die!""Are there better games in this genre? Of course. But sometimes I don't feel like firing up an Egosoft title and micro-managing a fleet of traders. Sometimes I just want to have a little fun. Rebel Galaxy was made for those times."
