,Recommended,290300,34160029,Posted: 10 August,all,Endyo,"Right now, we’re in the heyday of the space sim resurgence, with new indie games popping up all the time and heavily funded titles being fleshed out every day.  Rebel Galaxy was one of the higher profile indie iterations that came out of this movement and it gained that notoriety for having a different sort of take on the way combat between ships would work out.  Yet for all of the special things it does, it also encounters some of the same pitfalls that many other space sims try and sometimes fail to overcome.One of the most interesting parts of Rebel Galaxy is the way that combat works.   Even in the smallest ship you get starting out, all combat works on a 2D plane that has you essentially moving your ship around like a sailboat.  Much like the battling in sailing tall ships of the past, you’ll have to make use of wide turns and adjusting your speed to bring yourself broadside to use your main weapons.   This makes for some very involving mechanics that have you trying to take in to account the status of shields and armor of both your ship and your enemy.  Your ship also has automatically aiming secondary turrets that can be set to track and attack certain targets or just left to default whatever target you’re looking at (which still works reasonably well).  These can also be taken control of directly if you want to aim precisely, though I rarely used this feature.  This combat system is really the meat of the game and what keeps it worth playing when you’ve grown tired of the other generic portions.To dig in to those generic elements, the game has you warping between stations, missions, and various waypoints on its 2D representation of star systems doing all of what you’d normally see in game in this genre.  You’ll be able to pick up missions that have you beating up enemies of different factions, taking out pirates with bounties, buying and trading cargo, mining, protecting, or just simply blowing something up.  You can also freestyle much of this stuff by warping around taking out enemies with bounties, responding to distress beacons you come across, or attacking anyone you see and grabbing their cargo like a regular pirate.  It is very similar to old games like Freelancer.  This can be fun at times, but it’s always more advantageous (and profitable) to take missions that have you doing this stuff for more money.   One thing that makes free roaming appealing though, is that you can warp anywhere and turn while you are under way.  This makes the action feel much more interactive than in other games where you just fire off to a preset waypoint.  You can travel your own path.The story isn’t anything too special, but does have a story put together well enough to make the dialogue and cutscenes worth watching.  Much like any open world RPG, you’re able to ignore it for as long as you want without any consequence.  I’m not sure if the scaling difficulty also scales with the story, but in my progression I don’t recall ever having a story mission that extra easy because I took so much time off upgrading my ship and doing other missions.  Rebel Galaxy also features a solid soundtrack that includes bluesy and southern rock songs that sound fantastic and give the game a Firefly feel.  You can sort of get that the show inspired a bit of the aesthetic both in characters and ships being gritty and Western.  However, this soundtrack has many songs that include lyrics.  That is not inherently a problem in game soundtracks, but when lyrical songs are part of the main rotation of music, especially on longer games like this one, you really start noticing the repetition of the songs.  It got to the point that after about 15 hours or so I could not stand the music distracting me anymore and turned it off for some more instrumental music I enjoy.  Playing though the soundtrack without any repeats outside of the game lets you enjoy it a lot more than in the game.Musical repetition wasn’t the biggest problem Rebel Galaxy had though.  What had me raging was the seemingly random spikes in difficulty in missions.  Even after a bit of research, I’m not entirely sure how the scaling difficulty is determined, but the consensus seems to be that it’s related to the level of your ship equipment.  This means that even a relatively small upgrade of one or two things can mean either a mission becomes a joke or the enemies become so strong you are torn apart in seconds.  The discreet nature of this system made it extremely frustrating, as the stated difficulty of missions (ranging from “Very Easy” to “Very Hard”) may not at all represent how difficult it actually is.  This means sometimes you may just have to neglect a mission (and sometimes a story mission) until you can upgrade your ship to actually finish it – which brings to the surface some other issues like the general repetition of the types of missions you encounter.  Fun gameplay can only hold back the exhaustion of repetition for so long, so when progress is inhibited it starts to chip away at the paint.  Some games can pull of enemy scaling and it works flawlessly, but something went wrong in this implementation.In the 22 hours it took me to complete the game, there were times I thought this was absolutely wonderful and times I never wanted to play it again.  Prior to completing it recently, I actually stopped playing it for several months after reaching a particularly rough point, and I think someone with less patience (can’t be too many of those) would give up as soon as the newness of the mechanics wore off.  However, taking the game as a whole as I always do, I think it’s worth picking up at the heavy discounts it’s now seeing.  Rebel Galaxy is worth trying out for $6 it has reached recently at the very least, so I recommend grabbing it next time it’s on sale if you have any interest in space sims.  It stands a step above its more generic or one dimensional indie counterparts in the genre while still falling short of the more polished titles coming along these days.If you'd like to see more of my reviews, check out my curator page here:http://steamcommunity.com/groups/EndyoGaming#curation"
76561198024902731,Not Recommended,290300,23401885,"Posted: 5 June, 2016",all,iceman_63,"After reading reviews about this game being successor to the freelancer classic, I bought the game. The first few hours of game was quite disappointing as the 2D flight mode and the lukeworm story can hardly convince me that this game is even comparable to freelancer. After 5 hours, however, the game became a little more interesting as weapons and ships are unlocked and some of the missions are quite interesting. I have to admit the graphics are good, not superb, but comparable to the freelance --- a shame on its own as the freelancer was a game almost two decades old. The combat system was not inspiring but acceptable and admittedly quite fun to play. Just as I thought the game is getting better, it quickly revealed to me that this is no more than a freelancer game in its core repacked with better graphics and a toned down 2D flight mode. The game soon degenerates into a struggling effort to complete repetitive missions to gain enough money to upgrade ships and components that are ridiculously expensive and are so for no other apparent reasons than to compel the player to complete those stupid missions. So far I think it is unrealistic to make enough money to buy any of those higher level weapons and ships with trade alone. The difficulty associated with some of these missions are also questionable as some missions would see you quickly swarmed by a horde of overpowered enemies ships while other missions give ridiculously high reward for the simpler tasks.In conclusions, I believe this is a game suitable, in fact I would use the word ideal, for killing your excessive pastime at a moderate price. However, to comment that this game may even aspire to be of the equal to freelancer is a severe overstatement."
76561198006972472,Recommended,290300,24587482,"Posted: 28 July, 2016",all,bhutchsn,"Overall this game is amazing. As other reviewers have mentioined this game plays like Freelancer and the Assassins Creed sailing mechanic had a baby.  One issue for me: I did not find the soundtrack to be as wonderful as most do. There are moments where this game genuinely feels like a space western in the vein of Firefly, with moody slide guitar and banjo cues.  At other times, the music drifts into the realm of nickelback clones and pop country (even worse than Whedon's godawful song at the beginning of Firefly).  Personally, I'd ilke to see some of those lound country and blues songs toned down or replaced with a wider variety of background/atmosphere-building music.Other than this particular issue of taste, I wholeheartedly suggest you buy this. Best space sim I've played in recent years.  Combat is very satisfying and upgrades come quicker than you think if you go about your purchases the right way.   A small tip: don't constantly strive for a new ship. Instead work at upgrading your defenses and weapons. Once I figured this out, it was much easier to complete those high-paying missions needed to finance the next vessel."
