76561198061960277,Recommended,290300,35197483,Posted: 24 September,all,Alan Woke,"I'll keep it simplePros:-Nice visuals-Open world-Different ships to suit different playstyles-Aussies in space-Broadside naval-like combatCons:-90% of game is grinding slight variations of the same 3 missions to upgrade weapons/armor in order to not get reamed trying advance the story.-Larger ships have massive upgrade and repair costs mid to late game (1/8+ slot turrets costing nearly 2,000,000 credits)-Speed and positioning are huge factors in deciding fights, undermining any incentive to actually buy larger ships.-Even if you opt for long range weapons, the fastest way to take out most ships is to simply fly up close to them and spam LMB as fast as you can(Apparently the AI hasn't read the guides for this game on how to achieve maximum Dps)-Factions feel like they aren't fully fleshed out and ""rewards"" from helping said factions are lackluster at best.-Bounties(Other than lords) are seldom worth pursuing as the monetary rewards are usually a fraction of what a quest would give-Distress signals will often spawn behind you when you are in warp en-route to a mission causing you to have to come to a full stop and 180 and backtrack assuming you want to try to help.Best case scenario it's a trader who will give you a small amount of credits and not an ambush where you will gain ultimately nothing except for time wasted.With larger ships this process takes much longer due to turnspeed.-Escort missions have some of the worst A.I. I have seen in a game of this type.Often times when you pair warp, they'll fly straight into an asteroid field and sometimes if the escort goes on too long, the ship you are supposed to be escorting will just disappear(bug) causing you to fail the mission.-This game has a lack of immersion. You can destroy countless pirate lords and entire fleets and nobody seems to notice.Even as part of the main story quests, Npc's seem to have the attitude of ""Oh you're finally here"" and ""What took you so long?"" even though you are a single ship who just took out 10 dreadnoughts by yourself.Nothing you do feels like it actually has any real impact on the world (Universe?)Despite the flaws, I still had fun and would probably play a sequel."
,Recommended,290300,35025261,Posted: 17 September,all,shandlanos,"Solid title, good gameplay mechanics, quick progression.I'm generally not a fan of space games that restrict you to a single plane, but this game pulls it off. The transition between sublight and warp speeds is seamless, conveying a good sense of size to each solar system. There are some issues with scaling (small/medium craft with advanced weapons survive much better in the same scenarios than larger more expensive craft with the same armament and equipment), and the ""precise"" aiming mode for turrets is complete trash, swinging drunkenly past where you actually try to aim. Even the general ""manual"" aiming mode needs work, as it likes to lock on to whatever it feels like. There needs to be a key to quickly toggle between locking and true manual aiming.The main plot is fun, if short.This is a solid entry in the genre, and if there were a proper developer's kit I feel like it would attract a great mod community to take the game to the next level. It's been out for around two years and there has been no DLC and I've seen no rumor of a sequel, so that's a bit disappointing. As positive as all the reviews are, I hope sales were good and the developer can go on to produce more in the genre. There are too few space games out there, and few with such a shallow learning curve. It's very easy to pick up and play."
