,Recommended,290300,32172572,Posted: 4 June,all,Mephisto,"It's a cross between Freelancer and Sid Meier's Pirates! It's like Freelance in the sense that you get to upgrade your ship, trade, be a space pirate if you want and side with a faction. It's similar to Sid Meier's Pirates! as you get to go to outposts which have fluctuating prices of goods, have a bar in which you can get information and hire a merc to work for you and in-game events that influence how much goods cost.Let's take it part by part:Gameplay: It's an open world (or open galaxy) 3rd person space combat simulation that let's you be your own kind of spacefarer. Though you're in space, you can only go left or right as there is no up and down movement. There are 2-3 tiers of basic upgrades for your ship in the first solar system, and I think it adds one per system you go into (I'm not sure yet. I've played 16 hours of the game and I'v eonly done a few story missions lol). There are factions and so far, I've only encountered one guild.Story: I haven't played much of the main storyline so far as I spent most of my time doing side missions and getting money. I'm sorry about this.Combat: The combat is kinda tricky at first but It's kinda awesome once you get the hang of it. Also, you can travel to the next system as soon as you want and upgrade your ship enough to be really overpowered in the previous system. I have mining lasers that swat around fighters like they're mosquitoes.Graphics: The developers didn't skip out on making this game beautiful. From projectiles and laser beams to missile and engine trails, the graphics look great. The makers of the game didn't also skip out on the characters here, animating them with lip movements consistent with their dialogue (I really shouldn't be impressed with this but I am because they could've just put in a picture and have dialogue play in the background).Music and Sound Effects: Sound effects are to be expected in a space shooter but there's a small amount of dialogue that has some popping ""p's"" during recording. The music makes the atmosphere kinda feel like you're in Firefly (TV Series) and you can include tracks of your own as there's an option before you start the game. There's nothing like having beams of lasers shoot around while you're listening to dubstep."
