"" and other smaller subsystemsDiplomancy ImprovementsPaintable Ships maybe a custom flag editorAbility to create your own factionMore realistic astrouid beltsEach ship has a SUPER WEAPON or Perk"
76561198003716895,Recommended,290300,23370568,"Posted: 3 June, 2016",all,Partycrasher,"Takes the fun/addictive elements of freeform space sims while avoiding the over-complexity of some of these titles (such as the X-series). As usual you start with an underequipped ship and earn money for better weapons/systems, new ships, and even mercenary support if you want it. You can earn money via missions (randomly generated and storyline), trading, mining, piracy or bounty hunting; it's up to you if you want to stay the right side of the law or if you aim to misbehave. It's worth noting that your starting ship is a corvette and the ship classes only get bigger from there on (right up to massive dreadnoughts). Because you're always commanding a large ship, combat is very different from a fighter-focused space sim and as others have pointed out it the 2D movement gives a 'naval battle in space' feel to it (though faster paced); it actually works pretty well, making the battles very fun to play - which is a good thing, because there is a lot of combat in this game.Visually this has a beautiful-looking universe, some spectular space battles and a wide variety of nice ship designs (from Serenity-style rustbuckets to more conventional-looking starships). I like the fact that the different ships cater to different playstyles -  bigger isn't necessarily better as there are other factors like speed, manouverabilty and weapon placement, so instead of a linear progression to the 'best' ship, people will find their own favorite ships along the way.There are some aspects of the game that could do with some improvement such as the scaling of encounters and missions - the actual difficulty of missions doesn't always seem to match the stated risk level. Also it's quite possible to get into fights where the only chance of survival is to run, especially at the beginning of the game; though this is not a bad thing in itself, the fact that the game pops up a combat tutorial note on your first fight (even if you're totally outmatched) could confuse new players into thinking they should always be able to win their first battle. I can see why the single checkpoint-type save is controversial, but personally I'm fine with a single save AS LONG AS there is some backup in case of corrupt saves - fortunately haven't had a corrupted save yet, but would be pretty peeved if this happened after hours of play.The hillbilly rock soundtrack does help create that 'wild frontier' Firefly vibe, but it also starts to get a bit old after about 10 hours - fortunately there is an option to stream your own music - this is a great feature that allows you to select different music sources for different situations (ambient, combat, idle, station etc).Overall this is probably the most enjoyable space game I've played since Freelancer."
,Recommended,290300,23370647,"Posted: 3 June, 2016",all,Tratz,"Only played this game for 2 hours at this point but I'm seriously impressed. In terms of space exploration and combat, Rebel Galaxy is simple. You have one horizontal plane. You steer left and right, go faster or slower. Where the game lacks in flight complexity, it makes up for in very fun broadside naval combat, an engaging story and the freedom to make bad decisions. You are free to roam wherever you want and do various things at your leisure. The conversations you have with potential friends and ememies effect the outcome of the interactions. The sound track is AMAZING. Most - if not all conversation so far - is voice acted. Such a fun game."
