76561198027492858,Recommended,290300,32677213,Posted: 23 June,all,Lord Deurkruk,"Hello y'all!This is basically a game of Space Trucking in a galaxy that has something against truckers, judging by the amount of pirates involved. The gameplay is rather repetative as well, since you'll be doing the same type of quest over and over again.So why the thumbs up?- There is something deeply pleasing in driving (ehm, flying) an ever improving Space Truck through ever more advanced pirate fleets, some of which can be pretty darn dangerous.- The game's soundtrack helps in getting you into the right mindset, to fly through space and truck stuff from one place to another. And if it doesn't, you can change it to something else without hassle.- The combat can be pretty fun, messy as it is. Welding an opposing dreadnaught into space dust using the blind spot and your 4 front mounted mining laser turrets is also pretty amusing in a ""haha, you can't get me and if I'm wrong I'm SO dead"" kind of way. (Until you find a dreadnought that features 18 or so rocket ports at what you hoped would be the blind spot, anyway).- There are quite a few Space Trucks available, most of which have a reasonably clear use for your preferred style of combat.That being said, the game IS repetative and some of the achievements are a grind. But if you can pick it up at a discount? Give it a go.Happy Space Trucking!"
,Recommended,290300,23343656,"Posted: 2 June, 2016",all,changtau2005,"Basically Assassin's Creed: Black Flag meets Starfleet Command. This is not a simulation - it's more arcadey than even Starpoint Gemini, but it's better for it. If you like any combat based on firing arcs and positioning at your optimal range, or managing shield, weapon, and barrier cooldowns, you'd feel right at home. The combat in this game and the variety of ships, weapons, strategies available, and the tradeoffs you make between them is stellar. You can even build your ship dedicated to ramming stuff. Just don't expect anything from the story. Ships are constrained on a 2D plane with fighters and gunships having some leeway on vertical positioning.Your best time with the game would probably be the beginning, flying a hunk-o-junk trying to find your feet, running away from the big fish. It's a game that oozes identity. Do pick it up if you like this genre.One minus is that weapons and systems are tiered, so after you've seen all the varieties (which there are a lot of), the only way up is bigger numbers. Also, unlike some other games like X3, there's almost no variation between star systems, like alien installations or anomalies and so on, so the endgame can get rather repetitive.There are a large number of ships to choose from, but many of them seem sub-par; small ships do piddling damage, huge ships are sitting duck to swarms of smaller ships and cannot defend escorts effectively. The best ships are ones that can punch way above their weight class - and IMO that's generally the Barracuda and eventually the Minotaur, but they obviously only shine once you max them out. You do get 100% trade-in for anything you buy and that's a huge plus - you can experiment with crazy combinations at no cost.When I played at launch, escort missions later in the game were an absolute nightmare. Ships would path into asteroid fields and get stuck for an hour, or the tiny destroyer(s) you need to protect would trade broadsides with dreadnoughts like it's going out of season. You can't even reach them in the fastest ship before they blow up. There were a large series of patches addressing such things - hopefully the silly escort AI / pathfinding are gone by now."
