76561198003787583,Recommended,290300,18637551,"Posted: 23 October, 2015",all,InSpades,"Intial thoughts and ramblings from a browncoat...Well played, sir, well played...  While brief, the intro has all the feel of a Firefly episode.  It gets straight to the point in a no frills sort of way.  Definitely hits the nostalgia right between the eyes.  The music genre and selection is a nice touch.  I am enjoying the story line so far.  The credit grind outside the story line can get a little tedious after a while, but if pays to have a 500k credit nest egg when you leave the first sector.  These aren't your Han Solo type of characters that you are working with in the storyline...  More like the type that Jabba feeds to the sarlaac.  Even the good guys are more of a shade of grey.  Outside of you (depending on your game play,) I have yet to encounter one white knight in the story.The chat option selected does not appear to have any bearing on the storyline.  You still go to all the same story line misisons.  (Even the AAA titles have yet to get this figured out, so I am not going to knock this game for it.)The controls are a bit different than what I am used to, but seem easy enough to adapt to.  Can't tell you how many times I have absent mindedly fired missiles when I was first starting out.  The militia don't like it when you do that.For those new to the game like I am, I suggest immediately running off the beaten path and trade between the stations.  Mining isn't all that practical, but the Mk2 Mining laser makes a great anti fighter platform.  You will need the credits for much needed upgrades.  Only buy stuff with red list prices and sell in places where the price turns green.  Taking missions off of the terminal always has a welcoming party near or at the end point waiting to kill you.  You can hire one wingman to bump up your overall firepower.  Freelancer players will take to this game very quickly.This game rewards caution.  If you charge blindly into a situation you will get smoked.  Sure you can configure your ship to knife fight, but a handful of ships will still mug you if you are not careful.  I found upgrading your engines, booster, shields, armor, and weapons in that order was the best option at increasing your survival rate.Friendly fire isn't.  The AI ships will go after each other.  If you get between them both sides will shoot you.  If you find yourself looking at a militia destroyer parking itself between you and a pirate, stop firing at the pirate.  You will only end up shooting the militia destroyer, lose massive rep with the militia, and all the militia in the area will start shooting at you.  Your starting corvette is barely able to fight its way out of wet paper sack at the beginning of the game.Rep plays a part in this game.  Outside the obvious rep for merchants, criminals, and militia, it is hard to tell how rep really plays out in this game.  Join a guild if you want to get your hands on unique ship hulls.  Getting the criminal factions to like you is harder than you think.  Missions from the stations are the easiest to gain rep, but even that is difficult if you are trying to avoid♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥everyone off.  (Yea, you got the criminals to like you.  Now the militia hates your guts...  and they have the strongest ships and in greater numbers in the starting sector.)Right out of the gate, I see a a couple of obvious areas needing improvement.1: The multi-function of the 'E' key can be a bit annoying at times.  You are trying to tractor an item and accidently engage the warp drive because you were out of tractor range.  Docking with stations can run into this problem as well.2: The lack of full 360 degree flight seems a bit odd in this day and age of fully capable space sims.  Those with the expectation of free flight along all axis will by put off by this.  It would be nice if they open up the y axis.  Your enemies and asteroids get to use the y axis, but you don't.  The station placement can cause problems when you leave the area.  Found myself autodocking when I just wanted to leave to the next station.  Probably my biggest gripe of the game so far.3: If you aren't aware of the tutorial help section, the pop up hints and help tend to come up in a manner of oh now you tell me.I will add to this as I rack up more playing time.  At any rate, it is a fun game for less than $20."
76561197970958877,Recommended,290300,18635977,"Posted: 23 October, 2015",all,Fres,This game is tons of fun and highly addictive. Love it :D
,Recommended,290300,20239537,"Posted: 2 January, 2016",all,nannerpuss,"Edited and update review here. I wanted to re-review this after seeing how good/bad the game was after you finish the story. I had a very strong positive reaction to my first 15 hours playing, but after you finish the majority of the main story mode, the game is basically over. It wasn't built for a ""sandbox"" experience or anything, as the systems get less and less fun as you move along the main story path. I'll explain that more below, but if you want a one sentence recap: good game, worth twenty bucks for sure, but it has a few glaring problems.First off, I really like this game. Almost every aspect is fun and it isn't often you get good space games on Steam. The price is good, and I do recommend it overall.With that said, there are some major flaws. The first one being the trade and economy system. It's so poorly handled that it's hard to justify it being in the game at all. The only time you will find the market scheme useful in any way is very early in the game, in the first or second systems when you are stuggling to earn credits. The work it takes to get goods and then find the station that is buying high is just way too hard to justify when you start earning $100,000 per mission - let alone when you are getting $1mil per mission later on. The 90k you might make off trading is insignificant. Your time spent grows significantly and the gains never justify it. The whole thing could have been alleviated by having actual up-to-date pricing information available both on the main map and while in a dock, but the developers failed miserably on that. It's true they did implement a (very minimal) scheme that shows you current pricing in each station from the main map, but it only works if you've already visited the station or happen find a message transponder that gives you the information. Even then, the information is only good for a matter of minutes. The game will randomly change the goods and prices in each station, so usually by the time you get enough of the goods to matter, you will never find the right place to sell it unless you get really lucky and accidentally stop at the right station. Couple that with random events like famine, celebration, tech boom, etc., it's like a lottery except the profit is meaningless. There is no logic or reason to the system, no attempt to mimic actual markets in any logical way. The one and only way to make real credits is by doing missions, which are fine and fun, but I think they should have either cut the entire trading system or made it universal and simplified. Instead it's like they started out with a good idea, but lost it halfway through.The other huge issue is the ""proximity stop"" system. Basically, if you come within a certain distance of any other object in the game, you will be instantly halted out of warp. This would be fine and make sense if they tried to limit the amount of debris and roaming hostile fleets, but as the game progresses and you meet more factions, the maps stay the same size. So what you end up with are huge fields of debris from battles needing to share a shrinking amount of space with asteroid fields and huge fleets of enemies wandering around. By the fifth system or so, there are a half dozen factions on each map. Then you have merchants and traders randomly criss-crossing the place on top of it, and they have their own bodyguards with fighter ships. It all adds up to way, way too much crap on the map and fewer and fewer routes you can take just to do simple tasks, like going to turn in a mission or finish a trade.  After the 100th time you get stopped mid-warp just because a piece of debris or friendly merchant came within 400 sm (in-game unit of measurement) of your path, it gets incredibly frustrating.It's also worth noting that the ""escort"" missions are mostly broken at present. They might patch them again, but right now only about 75% of them work as intended. The pathing is poorly coded and there are too many random objects that only confuse the AI even more. Occasionally you will get a big piece of ship debris and it will cause the AI's ship you are escorting to start moving forwards and backwards, over and over, in a loop. You can abandon missions at any time, so when it does break, it's easy enough to just forget it and move on.So, those are my main frustrations. Otherwise this is a great game and is easily the best space game on Steam right now. It's definitely better than Elite Dangerous, plus it's only twenty bucks. I got this on sale for $13, and for that price, it's a major bargain. If you are looking for trade simulation or a long-term sandbox mode you can play in after the (approximately) 25 hour storymode is over, this might not be the best game for that. I got over 30 hours out of it and that was definitely worth $20 to me, but your mileage may vary."
