76561197981904472,Recommended,290300,21022110,"Posted: 7 February, 2016",all,RYYX,"Rebel Galaxy is a lot like a shot of cheap whisky in a pretty glass, served in a grungy southern biker bar.  It looks attractive, and it gets the job done, but it has some glaring faults and limitations and can burn like hell going down.One of the often mentioned features is the sound track, I thought it was pretty cool at first, but after 2 hours I turned down  the music to 10%.  It certainly sets the mood, and establishes Rebel Galaxy as a ""Firefly inspired"" space western.  however it gets repetative, and is intrusive.  After you hear the title song five or six times in a row blasting in your ears, it gets old quick.I am susceptable to ear worms, and it's going to take a few days to get this out of my brain completely.   That isn't a good thing for me.It's not that the songs are bad, by no means, the artist who wrote them is talented, and I like the sound track.  But too much of a good thing can be frustratingly iritating.Other reviewers have done a good job talking about the games features and gameplay style.   comparing it to the ship combat from black flag, and I think that is a spot on comparison.   It really feels like someone wrote a naval combat engine, and halfway through decided to make it a space game instead.  This could literally have been a WWII naval simulator or something and it would have been the same game.   Just with water and islands instead of space and planets.To put it bluntly, this is an Naval combat arcade game with a space skin.  Despite this, the game works, it works stylistically, and the gameplay is satisfying enough to keep you playing.The game is only 20$ full price (I got it for 13$ on sale), and it's worth even full price, but only if you like the genre.Buy this game if:You like the Vibe of Firefly or Serenity.Like Arcade shooters in space.Liked the naval combat of Black flag.Like the standard Trader/Bountyhunter/Pirate/miner kind of space game, and don't mind the emphasis being on combat.Like the gritty southern/blues/country soundtrack.Like the graphics.Don't mind being locked into a 2d playing field, even when smaller ships can still fly 3d.  All around you.Want to control a whole ship using even just a console controller (works very well).You Like Single Player games.Don't buy the game if:You strongly prefer Simulators/realism to arcade style games.You prefer complex controls, and tactics (you can pretty much phone in tactics in this game).You are tired of the Trade/fight/mine paradigm of space sandbox gaming.You hate any form of country music.You Hated Firefly.You expect a long complex story with tons of twists and turns (I like it so far, and the voice acting and dialogue trees are fun... but it's not Mass Effect for example.).Think a ""2d limited"" space game is too immersion breaking.Prefer multiplayer.Final verdict:  If you like the genre, or can get past the burning in your throat, you will enjoy this offering.  It is a good game to unwind with, the fights satisfying the visuals pleasing.Like that cheap shot of whisky, it may not have the smooth quality of a higher priced drink, but it will still do the job, and if you drink enough of it, you won't even notice the burning in your throat anymore.Unlike that shot of whisky, this shouldn't give you a hangover, and won't ruin your marraige.Anyway, I have no regrets, it's a fun game, worth the full price unless you fall in the ""don't buy it"" category. )."
