,Recommended,290300,27583998,"Posted: 25 November, 2016",all,SMiThaYe,"The hook for buying R.G. is the combat and of course the ships because later on they are HUGE. You start with a fast ship for darting about but lacks fire-power and defence capabilities. You could buy a heavy frigate and become a tank but being such a big target makes moveability difficult as enemies swarm your location. Depending on the faction you eventually align yourself with (via paying membership fee), will result in access to exclusive upgrades and ships. Don't take on missions to harm a faction you want to align yourself with.A simple sandbox space sim yet entertaining and challenging to keep you engaged despite the short story. Camera view is in 3rd person for traversing the randomly generated galaxies - go to in game options and change camera view to +150 to see a lot more - when visiting outposts the view is oddly first person and this is where you'll: trade/missions/buy tips/hired hand.First time I played I didn't pay attention to the missions I was taking but you can abandon before starting. The limit of 5 missions was too small for such large maps and the thousands of solar miles needed to traverse. The warp drive is overly cautious so no worries about crashing into anything, be that rocks, planets, enemies or allies - I have however seen the Militia fly into rocks close to stations. The UI does let it down but worth looking beyond this, R.G. looks its best whilst flying.Starting off it’s best to pick your fights carefully as paying for hull damage is expensive. Thankfully there is no up and down to navigate (KB+mouse or controller works just fine) despite your enemies being able to. It adds moderate difficulty and variety to the play. Enemies don't engage until a certain distance but if you agro too many you can pull them out and take on the faster fighters first.If you’ve played Assassin’s Creed: Black Flag, well it’s that fighting broadside – R.G. doesn’t hide it’s naval combat style. If you died you reload from the last time you docked, there is no manual saving so ensure you dock before quitting. The music is similar to that of Borderlands series, all tracks are high quality and fits the game to a tea but due to lack of tracks it becomes repetitive too soon sadly.The game play does get tedious quickly but there’s more to the game such as commodity trading (simplistic stock market style) as this is the key method to upgrading/buying new ships when you get enough cash past the Mark1 upgrades, you could mine for minerals mid game to reap the rewards around asteroid fields as it's less tedious or steal a ships wares. Worth mentioning that the game doesn't tell you whatsoever the price you’ve bought commodities so have a pen and paper to hand or use Google docs in Steam overlay. Events occur in the galaxy that affect prices and there's a good guide on Steam via Reddit that details this.It’s a game that’s well received for a 2-man studio that runs on just about any PC, here’s hoping Double Damage Games next title is naval-based.( Sorry if this review seems short but this just about sums up R.G. in the few minutes I had to type this and as my first space sim. )"
