,Recommended,290300,18798217,"Posted: 31 October, 2015",all,Blazed,"I'm addicted.........That being said. This game is AWESOME. I'd of reviewed it sooner cause I instantly fell in love, but I've been unable to peel my eyes away. Every free minute I get on the PC, I'm playing this.It's a great semi-casual game that compares a lot to FTL in it's rougeness, and as far as combat and missions go it seems to take a lot away from EVE Online. There are other comparisons but these stand out the most. The missions and combat have managed to keep me just on my toes enough every time I start to open my mouth to say ""This is getting repetitive."" I get put in my place by some new tactic a higher level enemy is using. There is a bit of story line to the game, but It's there more to keep your compass from spinning as you progress than it to make the game linear. You could play for hours and hours and never touch the main mission and not get bored.I really can't think of much bad to say about this game. One downside that comes to mind is warp times can seem a bit long after you've been doing a lot of hopping around, but it's really not so bad as there are ways to negate it. Also, aiming with turrets at small targets can be a nuisance if they start maneuvering above or below you.Other than, a well spent 20 bucks. I've paid $40+ for a lot less entertaining crapware. If you enjoy Spacey, shiny thing. Get this damn game! You won't regret it."
76561198044619825,Recommended,290300,22379992,"Posted: 12 April, 2016",all,mcmorris23,"This is a pretty good space RPG. In addition to the main campaign quest, you pretty much go around the galaxy accepting different bounties so that you can upgrade your ship and complete the harder quests in the campaign. Almost all the bounties are combat-type bounties.You can also acquire money through trade on the commodities market, but it can be very time-consuming. The key to commodities trading is finding out what outposts will pay the highest for various products. For instance, a scientific oytposts will pay higher for intellectual property and tech stuff, but a rogue or outlaw outposts will pay more for illicit drugs and whatnot. You can also gain trading info by reading news boards and speaking to bartenders. Traveling between space stations and various parts of the galaxy can be boring. It can take several minutes to travel between points on opposite sides of the galaxy.The graphics are nice and the music is awesome, but it gets a little monotonous after awhile since it plays constantly on a loop throughout the entire game.The combat is interesting. It is ""naval-style"" combat, which means your primary guns fire from the side. This imposes a significant learning curve to combat since you have to fight sideways, which makes it harder to see incoming missiles. There are secondary weapons that you can switch to that don't require sideways combat, but then you have to constantly adjust your ship angle if you switch weapons a lot. It is challenging but rewarding when you finally get it all down.Rebel Galaxy is a fun and nice alternative to most space sims that require a lot of management and alliance building over a long period of time. Rebel Galaxy commences with all that by giving you a campaign and a ship. The rest is up to you."
