76561198022466405,Recommended,290300,23909910,"Posted: 28 June, 2016",all,Badrinath,"I think it's hard for me to express how much I'm in love with this game. The unique style of 'flat' space combat allows for combat to be focused on broadside cannons. The lack of a ""Z"" axis of movement allows focus for more tactical real time decision making in combat instead of focusing on keeping your nose pointed at a lead indicator like most space games.The music and theme are amazing as well! This is the frontier of space, so naturally theres an old west theme throughout The music consists of driving rock & metal rooted in the old west. It evokes fond memories of the T.V. show Firefly during some chords.It's worth mentioning that if you're looking for a space exploration game along the lines of the X series or Elite, that's not really what this is. This is a space adventure with exploration elements. On sale this game is an absolute must buy imo, but it's worth the current full price as well."
76561198012299128,Recommended,290300,23998279,"Posted: 1 July, 2016",all,Monk,"I like this game.  A LOT!  I bought it because I was looking for something similar to EVE, but without the malicious player base that EVE is notorious for.  This game filled that nitch nicely.PROS:This is one of the few games I've played recently, where the keyboard/mouse control scheme is every bit as good as the Console Controller scheme.    Intuitive and effective keyboard control make this a joy to play without a controller.The Graphics are Very nice, and Don't require a Monster video card to run.  (I'm running it on an old nvidia 9800 gt with 512mb of Vram and it runs just fine.  Framerate rarely drops below 60fps, unless I turn on depth of field and motion blur.  Then it still plays fine until I get into a nebula, where my framerate starts to crawl with certain effects, so I would recommend playing with those two settings turned off if you are using a lower end video card.The story is interesting enough and the voice acting is well done.The combat is where this Game really really shines.  It's very well executed, with controls that feel natural and fluid, and the explosions when enemy ships pop are extremely satisfying.The 'Missions' section of the game  is well set up and fun to play.  Mining works fine, and trading is functional enough.You can hire a mercenary (only one at a time) to fly with you and help you fight, and early in the game, they are quite strong.This game has a really cool feature called 'warp pairing' where you escort a ship by moving up in a flanking position and select the 'enable warp pairing' feature, that basicly causes you to follow the lead ship through warp while staying in formation  (sort of like gang warping in EVE online)  It works well most of the time, however, asteroid fields and such can cause the ship you're escorting to get a little confused sometimes.  It's still fun to do though and is a nice change from the typical; ""Go here and kill everything."" type missions.Cons:One of the biggest Cons for me is the difficutly system.  It is based on a number of factors, (Star system, equipment grade, ship type, etc) and it works well early on.  However around the later part of the second system and beyond, the difficulty gets a bit unstable.  You will run into large difficulty spikes that seem to come out of nowhere.  It leaves the game feeling a little unpolished, and can be frustrating.  (in the second system, I was using all Mark III equipment and weapons, and I got a Mark IV mining laser from an enemy drop so I popped it on... and promptly got blown up over and over again until I took that little booger back off again.  Adding that one cheesy mining laser pushed me up into a higher difficulty bracket and made doing even simple missions very difficult or even impossible.  My advice?  Don't upgrade weapons one at a time.  Save your money and do them all at once so you actually have the firepower to take on that next difficulty bracket.)Trading can be profitable, but is a bit clunky.  There is no realtime feed telling you what prices are in various stations/systems so the only way to see if you will make a profit is to physically go there and look for yourself.  A live feed (or at the very least a price list that updates once a day or so, would be a huge help, and would save the player from making tons of wasted trips to stations.)One of the few things I dislike about the keyboard/mouse setup is what I call; ""the-one-press-wonder-key"".  The 'E' key does various things depending what is available at the moment.  The problem lies with the fact that if several options are open at the same time, the key starts popping from one option to another as you fly close to them.  I've been caught trying to 'tractor beam' some loot into my hold and had the prompt switch as I'm pressing the key so that instead of getting the loot, I warp away.  Same thing when trying to loot while close to a station.  You end up docking instead of looting.  This happens alot and is pretty frustrating sometimes.Enemies tend to spam really annoying weapons at you when you move beyond the first area.  Leach missles and mines that screw up your engines and shields are used constantly in the later game and they are quite irritating.  There are ways to protect yourself to an extent, but they require precious component slots to equip, and most ships don't have enough space for all the systems you will need.Verdict:Even with the Cons mentioned above, I find this game very fun (I've spent over 300 hours on Rebel Galaxy at the time of this writing) and I would recommend it to anyone looking for a Space ship game based around Capital ship combat and broadside bombardments!  There's nothing as satisfying as scraping hulls with an enemy ship and unleashing your Broadsides into it!  Amazing!"
