76561198084098073,Recommended,290300,33822944,Posted: 26 July,all,TheKevolution,"Well, I've put in a few hours on this now, so thought I'd commit a few words here to give my impressions.What we have here is not a traditional space simulator. There is no three-axis movement by your own vessels, instead you move along the ""galactic plane"", giving the whole thing a very classic space opera feel. This is accentuated by the choice of graphic and audio design. The bulky ship designs echo babylon 5 and the modern take on Battlestar Galactica, whilst the gorgeous space-scapes and lighting effects feel like direct descendants of Babylon 5 and the Star Trek movies.The choice of combat along a single plane actually works quite well, giving the battles a naval feel that echoes that of the earlier Star Trek movies.And then there's the music, a forlorn, western vibe carrying throughout that echoes Firefly as much as it does Red Dead Redemption. All in all, the sense of immersion off these factors alone is fantastic, so how does it play?Very well, if truth be told. As is so often the case, there is a plot to be followed and plenty of side-objectives to keep a player occupied. These can be straight mining or trading, or can be more comabatative, by taking on various missions or engaging in a bit of bounty hunting (or piracy, if that's your thing).There's plenty of scope when it comes to upgrading your ships and you'll be doing this a lot. At the end of the day, it is possible to develop effective strategies that will help you take down somewhat more impressive vessels in combat, but there's a limit to this and you will want bigger ships to take down your bigger objectives.The 2D style of combat won't suit everyone, especially not those who are used to barreling through three-axis engagements from other games, but for capital ship combat I feel it works quite well and it still allows for engaging battles. to succeed will require an amount of grinding, but rarely have I enjoyed the grind as much as I do here.Frankly, this has risen to occupy the top-cluster of my Steam purchases and I can see myself dipping in and out of this for some time to come."
,Recommended,290300,33785950,Posted: 25 July,all,edward.hunter,"As a fan of games like Freelancer, Endless Space and other space genre games that allow a broad range of freedom, it's been a bit of a dry spell.  Though I am not completely done with the main story line, I am pleased to report - the drought has ended as Rebel Space comes - guns blazing - onto the scene.  And it supports and runs nicely on OSX? Nice.The game has style, and the storyline evolves really nicely - it gets you into the action, and moves you along at a pace that feels natural.  You don't start out feeling like a newb, but you definitely do get a sense that you are benefitting directly from your experiences as a ship captain in a galaxy full of character and adventure.Be patient though.  Don't be discouraged if you run into early challenges or even get blown away a couple times.  The game elegantly saves every time you visit a station - and I recommend you do so frequently as new challenges to your ability as a pilot await beyond each new jumpgate.The graphics and interfaces are acceptable - and I mean that in a very good way.  While they don't introduce any new ground to the space genre, the UI, controls and navigation nonetheless quickly become muscle memory driven, allowing you to focus on piloting your ship.    At first, I thought the 2D plane and forced third person view would render the game arcade-like, and limit strategy and tactics, but frankly, these guys have done an amazing job and tbh, I didn't even realize the combat plane was 2d.In short, Rebel Space is the old school, choose your own path space game we've been missing for years, and this reviewer hopes the folks at Double Damage continue to evolve this great new franchise."
