,Recommended,290300,33894662,Posted: 29 July,all,Eranderil Nix Grey,"So. It is rare for me to find the need to write a review. (Especially not the day of purchase.) Generally a game has to grab me. Rebel Galaxy... has certainly done that. I was skeptical at the outset- a 20 dollar plane-locked space game? Hm. The ad hooked me though, and I finally gave in and bought it.The first thing I noticed was how GOOD the game feels. The controls take some adjustment- it plays like the ship battles from Assasins Creed 3. But every single time I light up my hyperdrive it puts a smile on my face. Combat is SERIOUSLY fast paced, but flexible.Missions are about what you would expect from a game like this, but they do pay well. It can be hard to pick a downside this early- this is my first day playing, but I would say that the game does not really help you get established well. It warns you within the first half hour that your ship is crap, but only helps fix it a little. It tells you, briefly, what you should fix. I could see this being off putting for new players. Also- not for children. A fair bit of harsh language.Ships are wonderfully customizable. Your guns matter- make sure to get ones you like. They can make all the difference depending on your play style. I am a bit of an odd bird with these kinds of things- I like to keep things as far away from me as I can. Until they get too close, then I ram the ever living ... stuffing out of them. With the customization options this games have, I can fill my play style to a T.Feels a bit like SPAZ 2, for those in the know, mixed with ship combat from Assassins Creed 3. Then given a touch of western feel (mostly in the form of music selection).TLDR: Screw that, I'm going back to play this game more.UPDATE: I have now played the game through to completion. I stand by my initial reveiw, but have more to add. Typically I rate a game based on how much time I get out of it, on a scale of worth it, or not. Having dropped 40+ hours in, and still enjoying it, I would easily rate this as worth it.  If I had to pick any one gripe about a generally great title, it would be ""unmet potential"". This game feels good to play. But there is so much more I would love to do, including, (without being too spoilery) getting my best friend back. I would love to have more access to more ships, and be able to fight some seriously massive foes. Crack starbases outside of missions, if for not better reason than gits and shiggles. A massive, customizeable universe. ECT. If ever there is a sequel, I will be getting it. Had a blast.TLDR: Seriously this time. With a few touch ups could be a modern $60 title, priced at $20. Has a lot more potential than is met in game, but is entirely worthwhile as is. Worth $20? Beyond a doubt."
76561197970604149,Recommended,290300,24033461,"Posted: 2 July, 2016",all,GFez,"Love it.I've played it for quite a while now, and I love what they have done with the atmosphere and the battles. If there was an expansion, I would definitely buy it, as I just completed the main story. I am going to play more, try other storylines, perhaps try a bit of trading and even a bit of piracy.So, the parts with potential for improvements:I wish there were more setting for the stupid mercenary ship, such as ""protect me, don't go running off on your own to die"". That's not really a big deal though, I can always get more mercenaries, they don't seem to understand that it is certain death to sign up with me.The missions have no deadline, such as there is in Elite Dangerous, and that means there is also no real rush. If you have accepted a mission, you can probably wait until next year before you complete it, no matter what the description says.So, I would like more rush, and more stories to complete. And perhaps a reason to get out of my destroyer and into something bigger."
,Recommended,290300,23354334,"Posted: 2 June, 2016",all,WTWR Zydrate,"A space fighter/flight game is an itch that has gone unscratched for a very long time and for a very simple reason; They’re not terribly user friendly to start with. They're mostly varying flavors of spreadsheets and menus.Rebel Galaxy avoids this problem by... not being a very complicated game. It’s stuck on a single flight platform which completely omits the need for severe flight tactics, and is instead comparable to Assassin’s Creed: Black Flag’s style of naval combat, down to the similarly used “Broadside” cannons. After that, it’s a matter of strategically placing some of your turrets as they autofire at your enemies while you control one, usually some type of rapidfire thing to cut through your enemies.Enemy ships, usually the small fighters, tend to have access to the 3D plane which is not as much of a problem as you might expect as it usually just means you need to plan your position to open fire. Again, your guns can shoot them depending on placement.Meanwhile it has a sort of MMO-like questing style of clearing enemies, shipping goods, defending traders, as well as a story mode. I actually have a lot of fun just ignoring the main quest (As you do), running around making ALL the money, upgrading my ship, and having a giggle when my main quest’s risk rating reads “Very Low”.As an aside; The music is wonderful and it took considerable resistance not to name my ship “Serenity”. It’s got a couple hours of full length (~3 minute) songs that will change in space stations or open battles which helps mix it up a bit.If I had a complaint, it’s probably that there’s not too much to do mid flight. Mid transit, there’s not a lot of popups when you’re fighting thousands of whatever-unit-of-distance it’s using. It amounts to three things interrupting your warp speed: Distress Signals, Ambushes, and Asteroid Fields/Nebulas. Beyond those, you might want to stop to play some piracy and raid trading convoys that go between space stations, which manipulates the market for you to take advantage of.I just wish there was more to do when I'm aiming for an objective that's tens of thousands of whatever-unit-of-distances away.Ultimately, it’s nice to find a space game that I can be moderately good at. Everything is put together pretty well, and while some may call it too simple; I find it works in the game's favor. Space games these days feel the need to overcomplicate themselves, and Rebel Galaxy avoids that."
