76561197969131383,Recommended,290300,25807659,"Posted: 1 October, 2016",all,Sage,"I've had more fun in the first five hours of playing this game than I have had in a long time. Combining elements from many beloved titels across genres, Rebel Galaxy is what you're looking for. It's 2D approach to space combat leaves your focusing on tactical options and attacks instead of trying to orient yourself constantly like in other games such as Elite: Dangerous. Thatisn't to be said that movement can't be still be a challenge. When you add in the need to manage weapon types against mixed engagements -- which are almost always the case. In these clashes you will face one or several other capital ships and a wide variety of fighter and gunship craft. The former come in a nice mix -- you don't know if the next capital ship you are going to run into will be an up close brawler or a ranged homing missle boat. The sub-capital ships although substatially lower defenses still provide pressure on the player. In swarms fighters can effectively dodge in and out of turret arcs if they aren't focused on. Gunships, on the other hand, pack a punch in a small size. A group of these gunships can be as dangerous as some campital ships.I speak of the wide range of encounters the player can have but the variety doesn't end there. Consider the different armerments that any one ship can use. Will you use a long range anti-captial ship guns paired with swarm missle launchers or will you choose some beefy in-your-face anti-capitals paired with several flak turrets? The number of combinations doens't end there. Each turret location on your ship can be outfitted with a different type of turret. If you sesired, you could put to gether a kitchen-sink styple ship!Beyond the mechanics of combat Rebel Galaxy also gives you the freedom to choose the type of contracts you take on. If you are able to plan ahead you can take several missions and set up a somewhat efficent flight path. The mission types tend to fall into a few different catagories; courier, defense, elimitatie, dead drop (recovery), or collection. Although mission fall into these catagories as a rule, the way each unfolds is randomly generated to keep you on your toes. If jumping mission to mission isn't your thing or you just want a break, you can also do some margin trading or mining.The tradeing consists of transporting goods between locations in hopes of turning a profit. This seems simple, but a host of factors will influence your success or failure. The way time works in Rebel Galaxy has what seem like short warps between locations to having passed several days. This leads to a an amount of uncertainy of a fluctuating market shortly after you've left. Random events will also add a little spice to the mix. These events allow you to swoop in and pick up goods when they are over-saturated or drop your goods into a starving market. Ships in Rebel Galaxy also have a fairly limited cargo hold. So, no running around the system with vast amounts of cargo in your hold just waiting for the opportunity to offload it onto a waitting market.The difficulty that Rebel Galaxy provides is a welcome change to the modern status quo. Rather than needing to set a arbitrary difficulty setting you need simply get yourself in hot water by approaching a mission or location that's rated ""Risk: High"". This nice little warning suggests what you'll find will be a distinct challenge no matter your tactics or fit. At noumerous times during my play, I found myself feeling quite the force to be rekoned with. After rolling through enimies and dispatching them in a short time I presumred I was the big man in the system. Then I was ambushed in mid warp. I thought to myself, 'I've been killing everything iwth no problem; this area is probably too easy for my current skill."" I was so wrong. The three capital ships and a  few squadrons of gunships ensured that my growing ego was quite deflated. Although I could have, after being ppulled from warp, turned and ran to safety, I instead engaged foolishly and committed to a fight I couldn't win.To sum it up, if you enjoy space combat sims like Freespace, Elite:Dangerous, ando thers this game will provide a refreshing spin on the favorite genre. As you challenge yourself with different play styles and different engagements you will be rewarded with the uncertainty of your success while being excited to try again after your ship explodes.For a standard price of $20, I would buy this game twice. Enjoy."
