76561197972400735,Not Recommended,290300,33366081,Posted: 8 July,all,Isamoth,"First off, if you paid more than 5 USD or the equivalent, you paid too much.TLDR:So, I'm pretty critical of Rebel Galaxy. Yeah, it's not a AAA title or a realistic space/economic/mining/fighting simulator but we knew that going in. When I compare it to even something free like Endless Sky, I find Rebel Galaxy incredibly lacking in substance and just a shell of intentions to sell a game.On to the review:This is a bare bones sailing ship simulator set in space. 2D travel and fighting, silly economics with station events (actually one of the most interactive aspects in the entire game), barbaric ship speed controls that defy exhibited ship design or a semblance to reality, and a ship and equipment selection system that is no different than putting up a security deposit on the ship and gear you want to take out for that day (buy/sale prices are the same). It's great for testing out and playing around with various ship/weapon/equipment tactics but so unrealistic it breaks immersion and lacks any sense of investment or achievement.I had zero investment in the main story arc or characters because it was too short, flat, simplistic and superficial; something a 5th grader would write ( Mr. Guild leader, don't you have anything else to say? No? Too busy? Then why am I talking to you at all?). The naming convention for celestial locations and named characters throughout were a mishmash of Star Trek, Star Wars and other IP's characters' blended names but it unfortunately came off less as nerd cred or homage and more of a lottery scheme by the lazy. Mining was a joke, Commodity pricing and market mechanics were there to make a bit more or less as you sold your battle loot.There were topical side missions you could pick up as you progressed through the main story line which was nice and surprised me every time but that had more to do with my low opinion of the game than their quality (same mission, different skin). Rebel Galaxy was also graphically nice with flashy lights and explosions. Faction variation followed distinct racial design formula and there were at least 1 or two different hulls per class of ship for each race. That said, there aren't many player flyable ships and besides allowing more weapons or components, the ships’ hard-point layout, speed or maneuverability was more flavoring or player convenience than tactical substance. The sound track was good for the first hour then I turned it off and played space exploration, Brendon Small and Dethklock tracks in the background (Thanks reddit).Playing as pirate or one of the other racial's adherent could give you a different role to play but there doesn't seem to be any change to the main story line and your relationships (will they shoot you, listen to intimidation or ignore you) will change depending mission requirements if you've joined a guild and are doing one of their missions. This means it's easy to adjust your faction reputation even in endgame. That said, the only ones who matter are the Citizenry, Militia, Red Devils and Merchant/Merc guilds. The others are just slimes to be killed."
76561197986912394,Not Recommended,290300,19405346,"Posted: 30 November, 2015",all,the_moidart,"4/10Seriously, just get a Scarab, keep your turrets maxed out, and outmaneuver or out gun every ship in the game. It's just as combat effective as bigger ships, and much cheaper, since you don't pay a mint to replace 10 turrets whose coverage doesnt even let them fire.Pro:ShinyQuite controllable with mouse and keyboard once you get used to itVery SimpleCon:..Excessively simpleNo replayability due to every 'randomly generated' system being the same, with the same 7 factions, ships, stationsShort campaign with no feeling of resolution or urgency due to functioning as normal combat missions, only with voiceovers.Vastly underdelivers due to excessive positive reviews here.I'd say buy this game if you really want a playable space game, but frankly, you're going to get 6 hours in and say, ""Is this IT?!"" like I did. Maybe less."
