76561198118888431,Recommended,290300,20636454,"Posted: 19 January, 2016",all,feminist404,"Rebel Galaxy is a stunningly beautiful and smooth to play. The soundtrack really gives the game a ""space cowboy"" feel to it and I never tired of the music even after hours of gameplay. This game is worth the money.That being said, there is plenty of room for improvement. The main quest thread, while intruiging, fell a little flat with characters that I never really bonded with and an ending that felt... unfinished. The systems blurred together into a sort of ""sameness"". It never felt like I was anywhere new and other then slightly more powerful ships to fight, I never really needed to know where I was anyway. With all the ovious beauty, color, and art talent on this team, I was suprised not to see more planets and variety. Where are the habitable worlds? What about gas giants and ring planets? Where are the location descriptions on docking that make me feel like the places I visit have some personality? The ships, on the other hand, were done very well though, each felt artistically distinct and I enjoyed the variety. It would have been nice to have some variety in mechanics though. The weapon selection was somewhat limited and I didn't feel like I had to carefully equip my ship to survive. You either outleveled your opponent or not. I ended with an enormous capital ship, which was cool, but found I had no fighter bays. I found myself limping across half a galaxy while fighters far from my reach fired a stream of engine crippling torpedoes at me.In closing, this game has great potential. But, it could take a few tips from old, relentlessly addictive space trading and exploring games like Ambrosia's ""Escape Velocity"". Factions that matter would be nice to see. Factions with territory would be nice to see. Planets and space stations with some location information would be nice. A greater variety of technology, that you actually have to work hard to unlock would be super! How about some alien weapons? Cloaking? Or alien ships? How about the ability to board and capture ships? Have your own fleet? Dominate space stations and make them your own? How about... every once in a while... when your ship VASTLY outclasses some random bandit that warps in to fight you... they hail you and show a little damn respect?"
76561198029948055,Recommended,290300,20638149,"Posted: 20 January, 2016",all,milesprower06,"In short, buy this game if you're looking for:- Naval-style space combat on a two-dimensional plane against capital ships ranging from frigates to imposing dreadnaughts, ripping them apart with your broadsides while your smaller turrets attempt to deal with the fighters and bombers, while positioning your ship's quadrant-based shield and armor so the strongest side takes the hits while the weakened side recharges.- If you run from a fight just to upgrade and return to slaughter everyone later.- An endless supply of side missions to fund those upgrades.- An economy that highly encourages you to experiment with different weapons. Weapons, defenses, and components transfer to any ship you purchase. Don't like it, just swap it back for a full refund at anytime.- A game where bigger is not always better. Smaller, faster, more maneuverable corvettes, properly upgraded, will see you through nearly everything but the last set of missions, where your lack of 20 broadside turrets won't allow you to crack the shields of the bigger ships of the final missions.- If you don't care about a forgettable, anti-climactic story, because the rock 'n' roll and dark country makes you feel like an unstoppable badass anyway.- A checkpoint-based death penalty. Other than sending you back to the last time you docked, death has no ill effects. You will get a lesson in humility when you're doing your fourth mission in a row without docking, only to watch your hull turn into swiss cheese.All in all, this is a rather entertaining space-based swashbuckler that places gameplay and action above narrative."
