,Recommended,290300,21067824,"Posted: 8 February, 2016",all,d_anilo,"Rebel Galaxy is a fantastic value. Beautiful environments, perfect gamepad controls. The dog fighting is a lot of fun without being painfully hard to learn. Navigation is confined to 2D space, which adds some constraints to simplify gameplay.If you like trading, shooting and exploring in space, you really can't go wrong here. Progression feels really satisfying--your ship bulks up steadily, while challenges mount. It's very well tuned to keep you in the groove of difficult-but-fun. The save system is strict but raises the stakes of your adventuring and dangerous encounters--without being overly punishing.My favorite piece, though, is that the game lets you customize its soundtrack. I grew weary of the bluegrass after awhile, charming though it was. On a lark, I stuffed in my own soundtrack, drawn from Mass Effect, Battlestar Galactica, Babylon 5 and Homeworld 2.The result was so much fun! Shooting up space ships to the tunes I associate most with space battles was such a joy. Especially the Homeworld stuff, which is some of the best space music I have. The game is also smart about its music selections, pulling from different directories for combat versus exploration or idleness.This is a fun, lovingly crafted game that's very easy to customize to your exact musical vibe. If you like space, you'll have fun."
76561198042638761,Recommended,290300,21066263,"Posted: 8 February, 2016",all,Velos,"I have no clue why this game hasn't garnered more media attention. It is one of the most refreshing, accessibly deep, and fun games I've played in quite some time. The developers are sitting on a freaking goldmine of an IP. I fully expect this to be a Triple-A series in the future... and if it doesn't, it should be.It's like Eve mixed with World of Warships mixed with Pirates!. It's oozing with personality, looks great, has good music (though you can customize your own soundtrack if you prefer... BOB!), a high degree of polish, and the combat had me literally giggling as I perfected the art of assassinating capital ships and darting out of the swarm before the bad guys could react. There's mining, pirating, smuggling, trade, mercenary work, and plenty of upgrades all happening in an open world. It's a game you can jump in and play for 5 minutes... or 5 hours. Oh, and there's a completely competent series of voice-acted story missions in there too. But what really ties it all together is that it somehow the game makes you feel like you're the actual commander of a little (or big) ship zooming through space wacking pirates while trying to eek out a living and getting to the bottom of a family mystery.And that combat... Balancing speed, shields and armor, deflectors, broad-side weapons, point defense guns all while navigating a crowded battlefield is just way more fun than it should be. Not to mention the different ship types and weapon combos that lets the player customize their favorite way to conduct combat. Big Massive Missile Boat? Ok. Small fast laser frigate? yup. Fast and agile blockade runner? Suuuure. Do it your way.Im not all that far in but am just totally infatuated with this lil game. I say 'lil' because I got it for only $15 on sale ($20 normally) and yet it plays like AAA game.  The only thing 'lil' is the price because there's enough in there to occupy more time than most big budget titles.So to wrap it upPros:-Great Combat-Great Visuals and Effects-Open ""World""-Upgrades, Ships, and Customization-Customizable Dynamic Soundtrack-Accessible-Runs amazingly well on lower end systems (Which I have)Cons:-Movement only in 2 dimensions (Though it adds to the accessibility of the game)-Umm... it doesn't spit free cookies out of my DVD drive?Bottom Line. If you like space games, action, or fun buy it.A++++++++ would obliterate pirates again"
76561198007628459,Recommended,290300,21068486,"Posted: 8 February, 2016",all,LTdaz,"Great game. At it's heart, RG is a traditional space trading game in the likes of Elite, Privateer, X etc. What really stands out for RG is its deliberate direction away from the core sim experience of those aforementioned games. RG strips itself of the complex sim-y fluffs essentials of the genre, namely the trading, upgrading, fighting and occasional quest undertaking. Hell it even takes away the y axis, leaving only the ability to manuver in a 2D plane. Some reviews mentioned that the same isn't true with other ships and that's somewhat accurate but their 3D movement is still fairly limited (think the pizza box arenas of Star Trek Legacy) and for the most part your AI opponents ability to move above or beneath you isn't totally unfair. Also like ST Legacy, your ships are large size vessels not the turn on a dime fighters you would expect. Combat are more reminiscent of ship battles in AssCreed where large amount of capital ships firepower are directed to the side not the front. The music is worth mentioning in that it's not your typical scifi affair. It's southern rock, like in Starcraft or the show Firefly. The story is mediocre with some surprisingly decent voice acting. The production value is also unexpectedly high with good visual and sound. RG is also relatively bug free. The few complaints I have is that a lot of the missions are very cookie cutter, which is kind of to be expected considering the budget. The game is also fairly shallow, but the combat is visceral enough to keep it interesting for the 10 hrs I've put in so far. I also don't think the interface is as intuitive as it could be; took me forever to find out that the ship advanced functions are hidden in the system pause screen and not the command screen where I would put it. There are couple of similarly strange design choices in the game, but those are just nickpickings. The game is thoroughly entertaining if you ever fancy yourself as Han Solo or Mal Reynalds, especially for $13~15. You could do worse on steam."
76561198054044736,Recommended,290300,21068664,"Posted: 8 February, 2016",all,ccohen,"Have you ever been attracted to the IDEA of space sims, but been unable to figure out impossibly dense controls?  Do you love the IDEA of piloting a massive battleship into battle, but can't deal with stupid 3D loop-de-loops?  Do you just like pretty explosions and badass slide guitar music?Then this game is for you.It's a pretty standard space game setup-- fly around the galaxy trading, mining, fighting, what have you.  Upgrade your ship, buy progressively bigger and badder ships, rule the world, and so on.  The twist is that it all takes place on a 2D plane.  Objects float around and ships-- especially fighters-- fly every which way, but you only have to worry about one dimension.  The basic play is pretty much like Assassin's Creed 4: Black Flag.  You hold down the button to charge a broadside, aim a bit and fire; hit your shields to brace for impact before taking return fire, and so on.  There's a bit more, with turrets and different weapon types and hired mercenaries, but that's the basic idea.  It's easy to get the hang of and fun to play.  And, you know, it looks pretty, the soundtrack is great, and it's nice to have a third person view of your ship instead of trying to make sense of things from a cockpit view.tl;dr: If you want to fly a battleship in space without wrapping your head around complex controls, this is for you."
