,Recommended,290300,18604318,"Posted: 21 October, 2015",all,Butts McBellies,"A fun arcadey space trucking game. Starts slow, but really opens up after you leave the first system, with lots of equipment and ship classes to grind for. Though I'm not sure $18 is a fair price for the amount of content you get, I'd recommend waiting for sales.I do have some problems with its game design, though.1. Escort missions simply don't work. Warp pairing just boosts the chances to break warp from proximity to objects tenfold, and since escortees can't navigate space for♥♥♥♥♥♥and just fly in straight line, if you're lunky enough to get some asteroid field or nebula in a way, have fun waiting 5 minutes for NPC ship to slowly fly through it. Not only that, paired warp speed is also extremely slow compared to how you normally travel by yourself.2. Warp mechanics in general are hit and miss. For example, there should've been different ranges that trigger warp break for different types of objects. There's absolutely no reason why some asteroid or piece of junk should stop the warp unless you're REALLY close to it, it's not an enemy dreadnought that pose any threat. Jumpgates on the other hand are extremely easy to miss.3. Not only the UI is pretty ugly thanks to huge prompt icons, it also suffers from many problems. Why do loot and small ships have the same color on radar? When I use gamepad, I sit a bit further away from the monitor and it's impossible to tell what's a small square and what's a small circle on the radar. Why doesn't mission board show location of the objective on the map? Why can't you wave traders goodbye right after trading with them and instead have to go through all dialogue screens again? Why can't you just use B to go back in dialogue? Why can't you use starmap to check available equipment/ships on stations you visited? Why can't you see where jumpgates lead if there's a mission marker on them?4. Its's another game that treats you like a r-e-t-a-r-d and constantly gives you tips how to return to broadside mode, use scanner, etc. I don't need to see these tutorials a hundred times, nor am I dumb enough to forget which button does what. These things just clutter UI and get on my nerves, there always must be an option to turn those off.5. Systems lack hand-crafted environments and originality. Every nebula and asteroid belt is just a copy-paste of another one, all of the same size, there are no really unique formations and places to visit. Every system is the same, just with differently colored star and background. It's true even for the blocked-off alien world you get to visit in the end of the game. When you have only a dozen systems to offer, you could at least try to make them feel original and interesting in some way.6. Holding A activates tractor beam, docking, warp and opens dialogue if you're receiving a call. Want to quickly warp out but some pirate is calling you? Need to enter the station with full cargo but there's a bunch of illegal materials floating about? Tough luck.I mean, it's good fun, but these amateurish and obvious problems really keep the game from being as enjoyable as it should be."
