,Not Recommended,290300,20275399,"Posted: 3 January, 2016",all,Grape Juice,"Rebel Galaxy has a great soundtrack, and an interesting approach to a space shooter, but falls short.Unfortunately, the missions become extremely repetative, and the alternatives (such as mining) do not help you accomplish your end-game goals. There's no huge benefit to stopping to explore signals or distress calls. Trading isn't terribly lucrative, but does have shortages and surpluses to take advantage of. That said, they seem like half-baked ideas to a game that revolves around combat.Speaking of combat: While it neglects the third axis of movement and newtonian physics, it does 'borrow' broadside firing from some of the more well known naval combat games.Your end-game goals are combat oriented, and while you may enjoy a light, fast ship to pick off enemies from afar, it just won't get you anywhere further down the line. The whole game is basically a grind to get you into the biggest ship with the most guns, so you can complete the final few missions. The story is okay, but it's very short, and just isn't compelling enough to warrant that kind of grind."
76561198203388383,Recommended,290300,20275549,"Posted: 3 January, 2016",all,Dingus,"Super fun, very beautiful game!"
,Recommended,290300,20273923,"Posted: 3 January, 2016",all,Andrack,"This is not the Outlaw Star game I've always wanted, but its the closest I've played so far. Considering how almost synonymous the names are, I wonder if that's what they were going for.Rebel Galaxy is an addictive and light space sim. It has all the usual trappings of a space sim (bounty hunting, mercenary work, trading and exploration) but everything is simplified enough so you won't need to find a guide on how to pilot your ship or complete a job. If that sounds like a bad thing, go play Elite: Dangerous. I like how the system map keeps track of what space stations buy/sell. It doesn't feel cheap since it only updates when you visit the station and its way more useful than getting some dumb colored lines painted all over the universe. If you like dumb colored lines all over the universe, go play Elite: Dangerous (I like Elite: Dangerous but I use third party websites whenever I go space trucking, the in-game trading info sucks).Three things Rebel Galaxy has over most space sims are big ships, a customizable soundtrack, and a story. The game is all about piloting big tanky frigates and dreadnoughts. There's no option to pilot small fighter craft, but you can hire one to escort you. Piloting the ships is more like piloting a boat. You move on a flat plane and will be focused on firing your broadside cannons during combat. If you liked the ship combat in Assassin's Creed: Black Flag or Sid Meier's Pirates!, this is very much the same. I think its a missed oppurtunity that your ships are fully automated. You are the only crew member. A crew management metagame could have been cool and opened the game up for more unique characters. Being able to have a hanger that can deploy fighters would've been cool too. I'll give the devs the benefit of a doubt that they had these ideas, but scrapped them for budget or time reasons.The soundtrack is a cool mix of Blues and Rock music. Quite a few of the tracks even have vocals. The best part about it is you can replace or add to the soundtrack with your own music. It also lets you designate which songs should be played during combat, station visits, idling, etc. You are playing a lesser version of Rebel Galaxy if you don't include the soundtrack from your favorite space adventure anime in the set list (The Blue Submarine No. 6 OST is also encouraged). If you don't have a favorite space adventure anime, go play Elite: Dangerousand never talk to me.Rebel Galaxy has a story. It's just OK and it's there. That's more than I can say for a lot of space sims. In Rebel Galaxy, your Aunt gives you a strange device which turns out to be a sentient AI which guides you across the universe to search for things that will let it do a cool thing that everyone else wants. There are also ugly badger people who want to kill you. In Outlaw Star, the dad gives the protagonist PTSD and he inherits a sentient android who guides him across the galaxy to find a planet that will let her do a cool thing that everyone else wants. There are also sexy cat people who want to kill them.See? They're different. Now that I think about it, Rebel Galaxy has a severe lack of sexy aliens. I probably shouldn't recommend it but whatever, it's fun."
