,Recommended,290300,18727364,"Posted: 28 October, 2015",all,JRS86 shoostar,"This is a very entertaining game to play, albeit a bit short with a low prospect for replayability. The music is catchy, and the dynamics of the soundtrack system itself helps set the tone for different actions and situations throughout the game. The visuals are stunning, and more than a couple ships closely remind me of ships that you might recognize from other franchises, such as the Rebel Blockade Runner from Star Wars, the hoverships from The Matrix trilogy, or some of the capital ships from the EVE Online series. The game is simple, straightforward, and makes no excuses for being a stripped-down space shooter. The sub-$20 price tag is certainly justifiable.======================= THE BAD =======================- No reverse. It's all too easy to run into a large object (jump gate, station, etc.) and get your capital-sized ship stuck. Not having a means of reversing seems like a simple yet annoying oversight by the devs.- I totally agree with constraining movement to only 2 axis (it helps to keep the focus on combat), but I still feel like having a minimal range of travel on the Z-axis might've helped keep the ""hey, we're actually flying/battling in space"" feeling a bit more pronounced.- While a game with this structure might prove to be difficult to add this feature, I strongly feel that an online 4-player co-op mode would be excellent. Keep the game the way it is, but allow all of the post-storyline missions to be playable in groups.- STEAM WORKSHOP: The devs made it clear that they won't prevent people from modding the game (it is offline-only, after all), they won't be releasing any tools or utilities in which modders can use to alter files or create new ones to be used in the game. I find this to be very annoying!!! It seems like the devs are missing out on a big chunk of revenue by not integrating SWS into Rebel Galaxy. I, for one, would GLADLY pay another $10-$20 just to have this feature baked in. It would certainly allow for more replayability, as you can be certain that modders will create new ships, missions, weapons, systems, stations, etc. for people to play with and interact with.- The storyline and characters are WEAK. While the voice acting was done very well, the dialogue itself is extremely boring and uninspired, while leaving the player with almost no choices whatsoever when it comes to responding to an NPC's conversation. On the rare occasion you're offered more than one choice, it essentially has no effect whatsoever on how the story (or that specific mission) plays out. The main story itself is very generic and cliche, and will take you no more than 15 hours to complete.- I understand why you can't switch weaponry and defensive equipment while not docked at a station, but why can't you change system software components? Their descriptions clearly state that they're software upgrades, so you'd think that you'd be able to switch between ""Fracture Tracking"" and ""Optimized Turrets"" on the fly, when switching between mining asteroids and pummeling enemy craft. Nope, still gotta be at a station.- Warp Pairing: When you hire a mercenary, THEY follow YOU into warp, into battle, around a station, etc. Why would you reverse this role exclusively for escort missions? NPCs are stupid, have no sense of direction, and you'll fail these missions more often than not, simply because the NPC flew you into an obstruction and can't navigate its way around it.======================== THE GOOD ========================- Space ARPG: About 2 years ago, a friend got me into playing Diablo 3 (mind you, I grew up on shooter, sports, and racing games), and I've been hooked ever since. Being that I'm more of a post-apocalyptic and sci-fi gamer, the fantasy world of wizards, monks, and magic doesn't appeal to me very much, but I absolutely LOVE the hack-n-slash mechanics of D3. Since the day I started playing that game, I set forth on a mission to find a space-oriented ARPG that played out in a similar manner, without the grueling complexity of a more commonly found 4x-style space sim (read: Homeworld, EVE Online, somewhat Elite: Dangerous). Minus the co-op mode, Rebel Galaxy gives me exactly what I was looking for.- The ships are BADASS. Unlike Galaxy on Fire, Rebel Galaxy lets you play with behemoths. Shelling out tens of millions of credits to buy and fully equip a Blackstar dreadnaught is totally worth it the moment you take it into your first large-scale battle, and absolutely CRUSH the opposition with so much firepower, it's easy to forget that you're controlling just one ship, not an entire fleet. Even the smaller, quicker frigates (like the Barracuda or Tennhauser) prove to be extremely fun to play, especially once you get the hang of playing more of a quick-strike strategy rather than ""let's park here, and fire all 5,000,000 cannons at this target, on my mark.""- Rebel Galaxy is simple. There's pretty much no learning curve whatsoever, with the exception being learning how to effectively engage in broadside combat. I have 0 experience in this style of combat, but I felt VERY comfortable with its mechanics within the first 2 hours of playing this game. There's no complicated diplomatic or economic systems to learn, no micro-managing fleets and every tiny subsystem on your ship, no laws or rules to follow if you don't want to. As a matter of fact, following the rules and siding with the ""good guys"" (military, citizens, etc.) actually dulls the game down just a little bit. I much prefer to exit warp at every possible waypoint, fully expecting to engage in an epic battle as soon as the first NPC ship comes into range.- Small footprint/fast loads: This game only takes up roughly 2GB worth of space on your hard drive, which means when you hit a loading screen in this game (which there are VERY few of), you'll only have to look at this screen for a second or two. Matter of fact, I honestly can't even recall what a loading screen looks like in this game.- Offline-only: I already discussed why offline-only is a downside to this game, but I also see it as an upside. Once I finished with the main story, I found that I absolutely despised the notion of having to complete dozens of side missions just to squander all that hard-earned cash on gigantic platforms of destruction and be broke again. Quick fix: download and install trainer with infinite cash option, buy/upgrade all the ships you want. Instant gratification, with no consequences whatsoever for cheating.- Visuals: This game looks AWESOME in 1080p on a big-screen TV. Explosions are the only things that could be prettied-up a bit, but overall, Rebel Galaxy is a joy to look at. From colorful vistas in the backdrop of each system, to comet-battered planets and carefully designed ships unique to each faction, the devs made some excellent design choices in regards to the art in this game.========================== CONCLUSION ==========================I give this game a 7.5 out of 10. I'd love to give it a higher mark, but I truly feel that not including something like Steam Workshop (or some other viable means of modding/extending this game) is a HUGE detriment to the overall Rebel Galaxy experience. The bugginess and lack of any substance in its story and characters would drop the score even further, if it weren't for the fact that the game will cost you only $20. The devs set out on a mission to create a simple, stripped-down space cowboy shooter, and they accomplished exactly that, but certainly nothing more. Were this game to include Steam Workshop, it'd be easy to add another full point on to this review score just for that alone, even with a slightly steeper price tag.In the end, if you're looking for a game that's easy to pick up and play, inexpensive, fun, and makes no promises to give you anything more than what it already does, buy this game. It's certainly worth $20, although not a penny more in its current state."
