76561197968595270,Recommended,290300,18733546,"Posted: 28 October, 2015",all,Gonenuts,"Outstanding space adventure game!Ever since Freespace 2, there is a complete lack of decent space combat games. This new take on the matter does away with everything too daunting or complicated for more casual players, (target your target's target, I'm looking at you Freespace!) and adds the interesting poing of view of sandboxing it, and make it from the point of view of a civilian trying to make due.You don't HAVE to do anything, you can just explore, mine, find a space station that is not hostile towards you and make commerce. In fact, I was expecting something quite like it from the Campaign Interface of Starcraft 2! Gosh, your starting ship already looks like with the eponymous battlecruiser Hyperion. Of course, carrying away the main quests will lead the story further, but you can spend hours upon hours doing errands and getting into trouble on your own.It took a nice 3D engine to prove to you that in fact, you don`t need a 3D engine to make a fine space-faring game. The whole navigation and combat, despite you are interacting with 3D objects, is happening on an immense 2D plane, which is a whole solar system. And that's just the neighborhood. Speaking of that, no more disorienting spins, complicated escort missions (so far) or plain stupid tiny-ship-versus-behemoth situations that you can`t RUN away.Am I still comparing to Freespace? Well, yes. Let me add Star Trek into the mix. Since there is an element of RPG into it, you have different, and sometimes warring factions. But because you are not bound by those lores and canon facts present in ST, you can take sides with any of them, just choose your missions wisely.There is commerce? Yes. Mining? Yes. Online gameplay? I don`t think so, because you'd be chewed alive by any pirate-players, which I heard that's exactly what happens in Eve Online, unless I'm not out of the walled garden for beginners. I never played Eve, but that's as far as I heard, Eve Online is not meant for casual players, has complex economy simulations, and people actually invested tens of thousands of DOLLARS in building ships or whatever that game has to offer. Just bumping into these players would force you to play under their rule or face obliteration, which scares off casuals, like me.Somebody mentioned Firefly, and the look and feel are surprisingly similar with this cable show. But not knowing the show won't make the game less enjoyable.Well, in short, the game is a blast, no previous knowledge of other games required, no need for a gamepad or joystick, and apparently, which is not the norm, no microtransactions. Whatsoever. If you want the cool stuff, earn it.For the icing on the cake, the gaming is surprisingly small, never even fazed my dated Intel i7 920 CPU, or hogged down my graphics card, and allows you to just tell the game where your music stash is, and mix it with the own game soundtrack. Flying around the galaxy listening to your favorite tunes: priceless.Definitely, buy it. Worth. Every. Dime."
