76561198076230770,Recommended,290300,18711302,"Posted: 27 October, 2015",all,sweeker,"Decent title, I enjoy it.Essentially it is on a 2D plane, as others mentioned, but I find it not important in this case, since you are flying only large ships anyway - looking at Starpoint Gemini 2 (which fearures large ships only also but in full 3D) movement anyway more or less doesn't revolve around the 3rd Dimension so much, as in a game where you'd fly dogfighting little ships.Which brings me to the namedropping of Freelancer, I see al lot.It's not like Freelencer for me, for the same reason as SPG2: no fighters, no dogfighting, so you don't have the fast paced, zooming flight feeling as in Freelancer.That doesn't have to be a bad thing, it's just different.Graphics are shiny, combat is more fast paced than SPG2, although ship classes are comparable.Another namedrop is the TV sries Firefly, which I instantly associated too, but this vibe is mostly because of the music score - i guess with other custom music, this Firefly vibe would be gone.Setting is rather standard free roam space sim, with missions (quite some different ones with time and ""levelling"" curve), trading, mining(which I found very useless money/time wise, except at the very start, maybe there are good spots somewhere though...), a decently interesting main story and so on.The gameworld is mostly randomly generated each new game.The star systems and their availlable equipment are organized in tiers, comparable to SPAZ or Freelancer, at the same time there seems to be a different scaling for missions, which seems to depend on your overall equipment level.What I instantly liked, is the freedom you have in approach:You can pirate trade ships via dialogue options (you can shoot them too of course).Contrary to Freelancer, you can actually really play as a pirate affiliate and do the story at the same time.Or so is my impression at least, since once I had pirate affiliation, a ""mirrored"" main mission did pop up, I'm pretty sure i could have followed that main story strain instead.I didnt, because sadly the military faction will drop to hostile, once you are not hostile with pirates anymore and I didn't want to go that route... maybe in another playthrough.The title, as I understand, is from an experienced indie team, which shows at times - it is not as polished as some triple A titles, but it is solid and I didn't encounter many glitches, no gamebreaking bugs.And it's around 20 bucks, not 40-60...Some people said keyboard+mouse won't work well, but I personally don't have problems with that so far.You can remap the keybindings and using the mouse for aiming, controlling the camera angle works fine for me.The two most annoying things for me are:- the rather barebone save system. You can choose a save slot for your playthrough, so not to overwrite an older one, but the rest happens only per autosave and it uses only this specified slot, overwriting it constantly, like Far Cry 3.It saves each time you undock from a station, which works fine.And it saves when you leave to main menu - this is problematic, if you don't know this and save this way in a hopeless fight ending up in a dead end situation, where you can't escape nor access an old save.(I personally expect, or hope, this will be patched some time, to give more control over the saves, because it is really bothersome).I suggest to backup the save files (in ""MyDocuments"" for me) regularily.- the one moment, I really miss the 3D movement is, when trying to avoid obstacles. Semi-quoting futurama, in this dimension you can't step over something, you only can step around it.Other than that it's definately a nice time killer."
