,Recommended,290300,18821807,"Posted: 1 November, 2015",all,hijinks_the_turtle,"This game is absolutely off the walls amazing.  If you like the space cowboy theme of shows like Cowboy Bebop, Firefly/Serenity, or even the insane and wild adventures of Space Dandy, Outlaw Star, and Star Wars (specifically Han Solo), GET THIS GAME.A warning though, YOU FIGHT LIKE A SHIP IN THE SEA which means broadsides and stuff, BUT IN SPACE!  This means no going up or down or even do maneuvers like rolling.  Remember, you're a larger ship and not a light fighter or gunship.  Other than that, you can do so many things that aren't missions, such as cause a food shortage in a station and sell food for higher prices, indirectly cause wars by killing off a diplomatic ship, and other such activities (not going to spoil it).  Yes there is a story to it, but I think this game is better for those who like to make their own as they play."
76561197994522213,Recommended,290300,18821990,"Posted: 1 November, 2015",all,Kirsendarken,"TLDR: It’s awesome, but I have some nits to pick.I finished the campaign in an Arcturus with level 6 defenses, a mix of level 5 pulse turrets and particle lasers, and level 6 neutron beams in about 21 hours (net worth just under 40 million). My equipment level was such that the final set of missions was pretty easy (I don’t think I lost shields once during the final battle, and the mission itself was listed as low risk).Liked:Combat: I read some comments before purchasing the game lamenting the fact that it didn’t allow full 3-D motion. While I initially held some of the same concerns, I very quickly fell in love with the navel style combat system, which would have been difficult if not impossible to pull off well in a fully 3-D environment. From the carefully aimed long range broadsides to those exhilarating moments when you slam the side of your ship into your opponent and scream “Fire at Will!” as you pull the trigger as fast as you can, combat is an absolute blast.Movement: As an addendum to combat, the movements system in battles, especially when you reach the higher levels of boosters, is amazing as well. The sudden acceleration you see while surging along the side of a much larger ship trying to avoid its broadside feels like it should by squeezing you into the back of your seat. This, plus the broadside mechanic, combine to make combat absolutely enthralling.Ship Design: I really like the types and variety of ships available to captain and kill. From the industrial ships of the common citizen to the more refined combat ships of the militia to the strange and futuristic designs of the alien races, there is a very nice variety of ship designs in the game. There hasn’t been one ship that I’ve looked at and haven’t said “Oooooo, I wanna fly THAT!”Ship to Ship Scale: I really like how ship scale progresses in the game as you earn enough credits to purchase larger and larger vessels. You start off as a small ship trying to make it in the big leagues, desperately firing your boosters in an attempt to avoid a larger vessel’s broadside while keeping him under fire from your own. Later on you become that larger ship, trying to turn fast enough to keep that pesky fly in your sights before his constant fire wears through your shields. Seeing ships I used to pilot seem as gnats compared to my current ships really hammers home the progression I’ve made in the game.The 'Risk' System: It may seem minor, but I really like the risk announcement. Hearing ""Threat Level: Red"" made my booster finger start to itch almost uncontrollably.Music: Makes it feel like I’m playing Firefly the Game. Enough said.Didn’t Like:Warp Inhibition: Warp inhibition by stellar mass seems to be a bit finicky. I often found myself being inhibited by smaller asteroids when I had a clear path through a field, getting back into warp, and then later in the trip having to jerk to the side to avoid a much larger asteroid whose surface I would barely skim while remaining in warp without a problem. I overall like the inhibition system, but it seems it could use some tweaking.Emptiness: I wasn’t exactly sure what to label this one. Basically, it felt that systems lacked traffic where you would expect it to be, and as a result the game felt a bit emptier then it should have. For example, I never encountered another ship around a jumpgate (except for the last story sequence, of course). Freelancer had a very good system in this respect, in that jumgates always had traffic moving through them, sometimes even enough that the player had to wait in line! Some of my best memories of that game were running from an enemy I couldn’t defeat and hoping that I would avoid the dreaded “entering queue” and be able to complete the jump sequence before my hull failed. Speaking of which…Ease of Escape: I felt it was a bit easy to escape from enemies that outclassed you. Shields recharging under deflectors combined with the fact that broadside don’t fire forward by nature meant that it was trivially easy to escape any situation. I think I died a total of twice in the 20 hours I played, and that was only because I made a conscious decision not to run when I knew I should have. I really feel that there is a missed opportunity in dramatic escapes here.Story: The story had an interesting premise but fell too quickly, in my opinion, into ‘save the world’ mode. I had hoped the story would focus more on “space wild west” type themes, like the conflict between the civilized core worlds and the wild frontier or between an expanding colonial power and those resisting that expansion. I could see hints of the latter in the story, but it ended up feeling more like a mass effect type overarching plot, which I felt fit the lore and feel of the game less well.With all that said, I want to reiterate how much I really like Rebel Galaxy. It’s a fun, fast paced game with an awesome soundtrack and even better combat. I’m really interested to see where the developers take it from here and will almost certainly be purchasing whatever they create next."
