76561198198213381,Recommended,290300,19242200,"Posted: 23 November, 2015",all,Trigunman,"Man, eat your heart out Han Solo!  Space adventure and star-RPG action not seen IMHO since the likes of Freelancer.  Great soundtrack, lots of gratutious space battles, arcade-like control, plenty of alien races to blast into the next dimension.  The controls, while a bit awkward at first to me, after a while they became intuitive and better than I'd say Freelancer's was...  And I'm an old sk00l die-hard Freelancer fan.The star systems are beautiful and actually laid out like a real star system, orbit paths shown and all,(via the map mind you) something I always wished Freelancer had done, instead of being static planets laid in a ""small"" star system.The attention to detail of the ships is great and you can even see ""scarring"" of battle damage done to your ship in realtime.  These things really give the feel to the game to make it truly a space sim.The dynamic economy and persistant universe features are also great features I loved from Freelancer are well done here also.  There are many many things done in Rebel Galaxy I had always wished Freelancer would be, but sadly it's no where near the depth and ""size"" of it.So with that said, the game is not without flaws though, It's story line is interesting and engaging, but also very short.  There is only a total of 14 solar systems in this game to explore, last I remember vanilla Freelancer had about 40-50 of them, some mods had an upwards of over 150 systems! (Crossfire 2.0)  Far too small of a universe to explore IMHO.While you do eventually upgrade to bigger and badder ships, sadly IMHO the name of the game is speed in these space battles and most of the big boys are far too slow to stay alive.  To me the only ""big ship"" to upgrade to is the Blackgate, (the biggest dreadnaught there is!) anything less and if you're overwhelmed, you simply won't be able to weather the assault or run from them.  Your upgrades, defenses and weapons are far more of an important factor in survival here as well as your tactics.(and hire a friggin' Merc fighter pilot!)As far as the BGM, I did enjoy the soundtrack at the beginning it eventually began wearing thin on me and I finally ended up muting the BGM.  Don't get me wrong, I love Blues Sacrenro and the songs are some of the best on a game's soundtrack I've heard in a long time, but listening to it for weeks on end?  Ahhhh, thanks but no thanks...In closing, the game has ALOT of great things going for it and I truly see it as a ""spiritual"" successor to Freelancer.  However, I can only assume due to the abbreviated schedule of the Double Damage team limited them to  what they were able to cram into the game is that sadly it's nowhere near of the likes of it's predecessors like Eve Online, the X series, Freelancer and so forth.  Therefore I feel you'll get your money's worth, but this is only if you're looking for something ""entry level"" in a space sim as this game is very approachable to casual gamers I'd say.  Try it for the space sim, stay for it's ""arcade-like"" action."
