76561198034430113,Recommended,290300,24401677,"Posted: 18 July, 2016",all,Thornaxe,"Once you finally have a massive ship, the satisfying feeling of melting smaller capital ships in 1 salvo from your main guns is exquisite.I found that throughout most of the game, it was much better to just upgrade shields and weapons on a smaller ship chassis. You can hide in a huge ships wake and whittle them down slowly where they can do nothing about it. This strategy precludes escort missions however, but i found those to be particularly painful anyway, and best avoided. The idea of larger ships not having access to any better shields than a small ship just feels wrong. Obviously the bigger ships have larger power cores capable of powering larger weapon batteries; it would stand to reason these ships would be able to field a shield drastically larger than a tiny ship.One feature i particularly liked about this game was the ability to swap gear. There is no penalty for swapping turrets/guns/components or even ships. Want to play around with different turret types and see how they feel? Go for it, theres no crippling penalty if you HATE what you switched to. I favored beam weapons for the reliability of damage, but YMMV. There is an advantage to a larger chassis in that you get more broadside guns and turret mounts, but is it worth the maneuvarability penalty you pay? Broadside batteries are a 1shot purchase, you dont have to purchase more of them as your ships get bigger. Turrets however, must be purchased individually, so that larger ship wont be any better unless you can put some decent guns on it. A huge ship with tier1 turrets is a ♥♥♥♥ing joke. Will that bigger ship be any better if you have to downgrade your turrets significantly in order to fill its hardpoints? These are management questions that i love dealing with and the middle of this game was full of them. Endgame was less so, but thats kinda to be expected that once you can fill a dreadnought class ship with top tier guns you ought to be able to melt fleets of opponents."
