76561198030798144,Recommended,290300,24403380,"Posted: 19 July, 2016",all,AncientRaig,"This little gem has got to be one of the best games I've played in a long time, hands down. Considering its been made by just two people, this game is worth 20 dollars. Heck, it's worth 40. The game throws you in to the rear end of the galaxy. Lawless land, pirates all around. Your objective? Find your Aunt Juno. How do you do that? Entirely up to you. You can become a do-gooder and side with the militia, or find your inner Captain Jack Sparrow and join the pirates. Or you can do a little of both and become a mercenary, working for whoever is willing to foot your bill. You can even become a trader, or a miner. As long as you're making credits. Work your way up from a lowly Corvette all the way up to massive Dreadnaughts. Or don't. It's up to you. Maybe you prefer your ships quick and nimble.What I liked:-Solid story. While it's not Oscar worthy, the story is engaging, and you won't be wishing you could do anything else while doing it. The voice acting is good, the objectives are fun, and it has a pretty decent length. It took me about 20 hours to complete the story, and I probably rushed things a little too much. I've heard of some players not even leaving the starting system for over 10 hours.-Plenty of distractions, done right. Unlike games like Fallout 4, this game does repeating side missions right. They're pretty much essential for you to be able to afford the gear you'll need for the story missions, but they never really feel old. You pick up missions at stations, fly to the area, and when you're done, you've made some cred, a few friends, and maybe a few enemies too. Each mission rewards not only cold hard cash, but reputation with the main factions. Getting in good with some factions is important, as you gain access to ships that otherwise would be locked if they don't have an opinion of you, or just plain don't like you. And with two joinable guilds, plus citizens, militia, and pirates to potentially help, you'll never be wanting for variety.-Progression, on your terms. The game doesn't force you to move to a new sector, or buy a bigger ship. If you want to upgrade, it's up to you to decide when. I went through most of the game in the Tennhausen and Sturville frigates, only bumping up to a Vanguard heavy frigate, which is my current ship and easily my favorite, at the last mission because I needed the extra firepower and survivability. There's a certain sense of joy that comes from taking out a ship five times your weight class and twenty times your cost.-There's 21 ships. That's a lot of ships. A lot of them are also very expensive, so the biggest, baddest ships likely won't be even remotely available to you until after you've beaten the main story, unless you enjoy grinding side missions just so you can roflstomp everything in a 17 million credit Blackstar Dreadnaught and the millions of credits it takes to equip one properly.-A living world. The world isn't just static targets for you to shoot. You'll come across traders under attack by pirates, bands of pirates roaming the black. Trade prices change regularly, and you need to dock regularly to keep up with the latest news on the market. Prices also change by station, and can be effected by different statuses, some of which you can even influence, if you're particualrly dastardly. See a trade convoy coming in to a station carrying expensive stuff? Blow it up, take it, and cause a sudden rise in demand for what that convoy was carrying at their destination. But be careful. Folks don't take too kindly to piracy. And, if you overtrade one good, or set of goods, a trade route can very easily dry up.-Random generation. Each system is different every time you start a new game. New planets, new stations, new fun.However, for as great as the game is, it has a few minor downsides, though neither effected my enjoyment of the game very much.-No co-op, or multiplayer. Now, while the dev team has perfectly good reasons for this, the lack of a co-op function in the game limits its replayability somewhat. This is the perfect game for fans of old games like Freelancer, and the ability to play with a pal would make it so much better.-Difficulty. It's erratic. When you first enter a new system, you'll find yourself occasionally running into ships that will utterly annihilate you, no matter how big your hull is. But once you start upgrading and reach the maximum for the tech level being sold in the area, you'll find yourself melting the meanest ships in the sector to slag for little to no return damage. If you're smart enough, and well armed enough, you'll rarely be paying repair costs. Using my three main ships, I died three times and came close to death perhaps another three times. That said, the game still feels challenging and fun, and enemies by and large scale with you, so most of the time you won't be utterly steam rolling the opposition as if they didn't exist.Overall verdict:-Why are you still here? Buy the game already! If you're even remotely a fan of space games, you'll love this. While the combat system is a little different from the usual 3D environment space games give us to play in, there's nothing more satisfying than giving a pirate dreadnaught a nice neutron laser broadside, and the variety of ships, solid mechanics, good story, and living surroundings will give you plenty to do."
