76561197986889783,Not Recommended,290300,23420815,"Posted: 6 June, 2016",all,Lex,"You know those games where the AI ​​programming can translate into the failure to understand the basic principles of math and funny? This is one of those games. The first ground of frustration you'll have it when there will be clear that the most powerful enemies in the game are not the capital ship of any class they belong. The only opponents that you will still have to look at are the small (or large) interceptor groups. These aircrafts are the only ones that can be moved in a three dimensional space, then eluding the most of your turrets (normally located in the upper part of the hull). They shoot almost continuously, surpassing the cast limits theoretically imposed by their weapons. But in this game when mentioning the limits, they mean just those imposed to you. Because whatever happens, the AI continue to cheat. The missiles at their disposal are endless. Useless to try to set any kind of strategy. The only work that is always the same. Remain as much as possible to the edge of the battle, dividing the enemy troops and then destroy them gradually. So if you can not resist the temptation to buy this title, expect a generator of missions that does not take into account your points of damage or defense (missions reported as low risk where it will be easy to explode), an AI that uses cheating, and be prepared repeating the same mission several times. There is only one real challenge, which is to figure out after how many hours of play you will want to move on.Maybe someone will think that I could have written that it is a shame because this game has the potentialities. But I do not think that's true. The strength of this game should be the gameplay, that if it were not limited by the reality of the facts, it would be pure adrenaline. Instead it is frustrating the most of the time. The game's soundtrack is undoubtedly the only note of color that distinguishes this title from many others. For the rest in terms of concept, I can not define Rebel Galaxy as innovative and original even."
,Recommended,290300,23443411,"Posted: 7 June, 2016",all,zanglebert,"This game came completely out of nowhere for me. Didn't hear of its release, didn't know what to think of it, bought it on a whim. Turns out, this is one of the most fun semi-casual games I've played in a long time. Some people compared it to Elite, others to Pirates -- but in my opinion, by far the closes is Origin's old Privateer series, which I played for hours and hours.At first, the controls (especially the broadside firing mechanism) can be a bit unintuitive, but it only take a bit of playing to get used to it. Also, while the graphics are 3D, the player ship only moves in 2D (as in: your ""height"" is fixed). Initially that bothered me, but now I actually like it. It makes the game a bit more arcade-y, without dumbing it down too much (combat can still be extremely challenging).In summary: unconditional recommendation to give this game a try."
