76561198076308694,Recommended,290300,23402906,"Posted: 5 June, 2016",all,redwolf,"So no more running; I aim to misbehave. - Mal, FireflyI had this game on my wishlist for quite some time and I honestly couldn't bring myself to buy it. I do enjoy spacey-shootey things, but that whole 'it's kinda like naval warfare' gameplay was not really convincing me. So it was on sale several times, and every time I saw that 'game on sale' email I was like 'yay' and then 'oh, rebel galaxy, hm'. Finally, a few days ago I was so bored that I thought I'd give it a try, keeping in mind the lenient return policy, so what could go wrong?Well, for starters, I was wrong. This game is more fun you than I could have ever imagined, especially for that price.But let's begin with the cons, since that is always what I like to read first. While the graphics are really nice, the character models are sub-par. Then again, they might have invented cloning in that universe, so it might be perfectly natural to have a gazillion space stations with the same bartender. or he's working more than other people. Bartending doesn't pay much, after all, so yay for realism.It also is a bit  of a grind to get started, no way of cheating your way to a better ship. While that is not necessarily a con, it does mean that you spend your first few hours desperately trying to find a station that buys yourt goods for the highest price, or you do missions which dont pay that much in the beginning.My last issue, if you can call my ♥♥♥♥♥ing that, would be that I truly and honestly miss a way to see which turret is placed where on the ship, because you might end up buying something super duper heavy hitting laser gizmo thing, and then you wonder why you never see it firing. Well, you might just ended up placing it underneath your ship, and since not many enemies go there (they better not, the buggers), it's not of much use there.Now, the whole game is so much fun, I ended up playing it till VERY late at night, something I rarely do, simply forgetting the time. Want to be a fighter for good? a pirate? merchant? all of these? well you can, nothing is ever set in stone and you can more or less do what you want. trading is done well, a stations have fluid demands and you can't just always buy and sell at the same stations. 'Events' kind of help you plan a little, but not in a gamebreaking way. . So that keeps it interesting. Fights are fun and not always easy even with good weapons, sometimes you might need to run from them and come back later when you geared up. Special drops sometimes give you that edge you need, some special weapon or gear you cant buy, also a nice touch. The whole ship/speed/damage/defense whatchamacallit is easy enough to understand, but complex enough to keep it fun.But while the game as a whole simply works and is super entertaining, the soundtrack is the real selling point here. You constantly feel like you are part of the firefly 'verse' and boy, they just nailed it with it. Also, if you don't like it, though you are clearly weird if you dont, they let you use your own music to listen to while you blast huge dreadnoughtships to smithereens.Rebel Galaxy is one of those few examples of bought for ten bucks, would have gladly paid fifty."
