76561198111269514,Recommended,290300,19245514,"Posted: 23 November, 2015",all,gamr70,"TL;DR: Space travel, big ships, little ships, weapon customization, trading, mining, pirating, enjoyable broadside combat ONLY on one plane (no up or down movement by your ship). Story is so-so, but not what the game is about. Graphics are beautiful, runs smoothly, 8/10 I would recommend for the 20$ asking price, definitely worth it on a good sale.Rebel Galaxy. Now here's a game I bought on a total whim, thinking if I hated it I could just refund it. Well I put about an hour into it, and honestly, that refund looked more promising that enjoying this game.HOWEVER. On I played, and I'm glad I did.Rebel Galaxy story is alright, but I didn't honestly pay it much attention, and it lost my interest quickly, becoming much more interested in ammassing large amounts of money and upgrading my ship. Yuo start out in this dinky little capital ship that seems hopelessly outgunned when compared to some of the other faction ships. But get enough credits and start upgrading, and suddenly you feel like you rule the galaxy. Your ship can be customized not aesthetically, but through a diverse set of broadside turrets and mounted turrets, as well as thing slike cargo hold space, shiels, boosters, engine, armor plating, etc. Buy bigger ships, they're slower and less manueverable but covered in turrets and a hefty broadside arsenal. Smaller ships have less bang, but move and manuever like a charm, boasting high top speeds to simply work around your opponents.Briging me to the combat. As before mentioned, your weapons consist of mounted turrets and a set of broadside guns, with the number of each depedning on your ship. Different turrets excel at different things, from taking down enemy fighters, disabling shields, or blowing the armor plating clean off a capital ship. Your broadsides are meant to be capital ship destroyers, with you circling your opponent in naval-esque fashion and bombarding them from one side or the other of your ship. Although combat only taking place in one plane, it is very enojyable and rewarding to watch your turrets anihilate enemy craft like mere flies.Now not being able to move up and down may feel like a real let down, being stuck only moving fowards, backwards, and turning. But really, it isn't, once you open your mind to it. Space is still a very big place, and I can understand how adding upwards and downwards movement may be too much for some people.As far as space itself, the races have no real lore or background of any sort, and the game is definitely not one to get you any extra information on any of them. However, there is much, much to do, from pirating, to mining, to trading commodities between various stations that can be in various states such as economic boom or famine, driving various prices of various commodities up, or down. You could also just hunt various bounties in each system, or perform various types of quests for the different factions in the game, such as the militia or merchant guild.Lastly, I greatly enjoy both the graphics and the sountrack. I often find myself staring at the various stars and planets in the game, even being mesmerized by the movements in an ice field. For the sountrack, the twangy rock style fits perfectly into combat or encounters whenever it is triggered, fading in and out at appropriate times seamlessly.Overall, I would say this is an easy 8/10, with my only qualms being that sometimes long journeys in space can be a bit dull, with the only breakups being enemy AI that are far too willing to jump into combat they cannot possibly hope to win, and it is incredibly annoying to be halted from light speed because you came just BARELY too close to a stray rock in an asteroid field. Well worth the money I spent on it, and a truly great deal if you can ever catch it on sale."
