,Recommended,290300,26223457,"Posted: 25 October, 2016",all,GearsandCogs,"This game is awesome!I haven't played a space game I loved in ages. Grew up on Wing Commander, Starlancer and so on back in the day. This might revitalize my interest, perhaps I can find a new one. If I were to summarize this game shortly, it is a large capital ship simulator. You don't do dog fighting like Wing Commander. Instead you are on capital ships of varrying sizes from corvettes (small) to huge dreadnoughts. Battles are mainly about positioning, weapon composition and some tactical flying to ensure you aren't exposed on a flank.Regarding controls, there is NO NEED for a joystick. I personally played the whole thing with mouse and keyboard, the controls are fine. I'm sure a gamepad would work as well.A few general notes:- You can only fly your ships in the X/Y plane, no barrel rolls. I imagine this was a concession as true dogfighting without a stick can be troublesome since it involves 3 or more axes of control. Also, since you are in a big ship such moves would be unecessary as you are a huge target no matter your turning/rolls.- The ship and weapon variety is fun and provides some different playstyles, I really liked just after I upgraded a ship trying to optimize my weapon loadout.- Mission variety was ok, but some may be a bit tedious. The escort mission in particular can be quite trying, I'd stick to all the others.- Trading system is more dynamic than the old games, as you sell more of a commodity to a station the price you get will change. Other stations prices might increase in response.- There is a random event system that also affects stations in a system. These events may swing prices for certain goods wildly. For instance, if a station goes to war weapons will skyrocket in buy price. Other interesting events include blockades and embargos where a faction will prevent all access to a station. You can of course either run the blockade or eliminate it.- There is a bounty system rewarding you for eliminating certain designated ships, so destroying things when not on missions is rewarded. The scanner will tell you when this is possible.- Faction support was good but a bit rudimentary as it really boils down to be a pirate or be with the law. Games like Freelancer or I imagine the new Elite model these relations a bit more realistically.- Some faction have some VERY nice exclusive upgrades, which reward sticking to them.- Difficulty varies somewhat, early in the game it easy to get out gunned. Later in the game I found it to be a bit too easy once you aquire the bigger ships. Maybe I'm too experienced at such combat though, some people have said this game is hard...Overall it is a very nice package from an indie studio. I fully recommend it, even at full price. I'm not sure it is replayable but I got about 50 hours out of it which is really good. After the story you can continue playing the game's missions or start fresh and play as pirates. There isn't any new game+ though, and the story from what I see doesn't change much depending on faction allegience."
,Recommended,290300,26214263,"Posted: 25 October, 2016",all,Othello,"Rebel Galaxy is perhaps the best fun I've had in a game in ages. I'd been looking for something to scratch a persistent itch for a sandboxy space western and Rebel Galaxy hit the spot in a way nothing else managed to. It's just a non-stop crazy good time. Pawning off your weapons systems so that you can kit your starting ship out with massive shields and boosters, then using it to collect dead drops you have no business flying within a jump of at your net worth. Dropping out of warp into the middle of space battles between entire pirate fleets and escaping by the skin of your teeth as dirty blues-rock erupts from your sound system. Being ambushed by overly ambitious mercenary squads, and showing no quarter as you gleefully blast them into the void. Dropping into a station to resupply only to find an insanely good deal on live organs, then hurriedly jetting halfway around the system looking for a buyer before the militia nab you for carrying contraband. Refusing to trade in space slaves on moral grounds until you see how profitable a commodity they can be, then justifying your actions by telling yourself it's okay, maybe they're the alien kind.10/10, would be a leaf on the wind again."
