,Recommended,290300,31605727,Posted: 7 May,all,InfiniteMonkeys,"Rebel Galaxy is the first game in ages to remind me of the fun I had playing Freelancer.Yes, there are other space-sims out there.  And yes, there are other trading games.  Freelancer excelled in two respects.First, flight was controlled with your mouse.  Seems lame, because the mouse moves on a 2D plane while a joystick rotates about a ball axis more like real flight, barrel-rolling, tilting, etc.  And all the multiple triggers are available on a joystick.  But the mouse worked.  I didn't want a fully immersive flight simulator.  My chair wasn't simulating G-forces.  Flight had to be simple and intuitive, yet hard to master.  Firing weapons was cut down to strafing forward weapons and missiles, easily controlled with mouse buttons.  Freelancer's mouse control accomplished that better than any game before or after.Rebel Galaxy also uses mouse controls and cut out the need for 3D combat by making combat mostly broadside focused with automated turrets.  Why would a ship firing broadides need to do barrel rolls?  Perhaps RG oversimplified combat.  It did not have that hard to master element.  Once you got the hang of it, it was mostly maneuvring into position and blasting opponets in sequence.  RG did add Ramming Deflectors, which were, perhaps the most overpowered and fun part of combat.  A small ship with a highly rated Ramming Deflector could tear a large ship apart while remaining in a position away from its main weapons (or disabling them).Second, Freelancer had one of the best stories of any action-RPG.  Only KOTOR and a few others had a story that was fun to get back to, time and again.  You had to work to advance and the alien craft were spectacular and beautiful.Again, RG was really good, but fell a bit short.  The story was very linear and a bit short with a sudden finish.  Still, it drove you forward and the Trell character and side characters were engaging.RG was made by a small shop (two people, if I read background info correctly) which makes it an astonishing accomplishment.  Hopefully, this success will fund future, and bigger projects which are equally as fun, and perhaps even multiplayer.If there is one final aspect of the game that falls short, it is modding.  As I understand it, the game could be modded fairly easily if a tool for unpacking the data files was created.  I'd strongly suggest the developers spend a little time to make this tool.  RG will survive and be replayable for years if it can be modded.But the bottom line is this.  RG is well worth the $$$.  It is a fun game you can play more than once, as a savior, a pirate, or a trader."
