76561198073560898,Recommended,290300,31677135,Posted: 10 May,all,Captain Talus,"Now, I'm unsure how exactly to place this game. At its core its a slightly modified age of sail ship fighting game except space and with fighters and bombers and spacey weapons. I played it for a while and I have to say the most enjoyable thing about it is the aesthetic. I love the songs and the look and the feel. However, it has a couple of weaknesses that eventually crippled my enjoyment. First of all the progression system, starting out it felt kinda like a much Much more forgiving take on X3 or something but then I hopped a few systems in and I started to suspect I was in a skinner box. Grinding for money for slightly better weapons and gear that has the same advantages and disadvantages as its predecessor is a bit annoying. Perhaps if I had gotten a few systems further it might have ended and changed but 18 hours in is a long time to wait. The second issue I had was the grind itself, a lot of the missions turn to sameyness and the only thing that held on to a shred of light and interest was the storyline. The storyline was literally the only reason I kept going as I was genuinely interested in its outcome. Unfortunately I didn't make it to the end as I was beginning to contemplate the merits of death at the prospect of grinding just to beat the enemies getting progressively harder. Conclusively I can say I enjoyed at least the first ten hours or so. It isn't a Bad game, but it needs more variety for just Stuff to do and needs to cut back on the grind a little. One idea I had was perhaps making ships that deviate from the standard method of fighting. Like ones that have a forward firing arc, different cannon battery types for different arcs, and weapons that behave in a unique way like a ""phasor"". Of course alternatively they could liven up the universe a bit with more developed side characters and add some weirdness to the place to make it have more... culture for lack of a better word. Ultimately, if I had to rate it on the Angry Joe scale I would probably give it a 4 or 5 out of 10. It's not terrible, and with a little bit of love it could probably become a game worthy of any collection."
,Recommended,290300,31711676,Posted: 12 May,all,「Sgt. Birb」,"After playing this game completely, I have a few things to say.This is a very fun space exploration/combat game, with a somewhat interesting, yet short story. (Most of my time was spent doing side missions.) I found that once I completed the mainstory, I already had all the ships, and loads of money, there wasn't much left to do.The combat is very fun in the beginning and middle of the game, with genuine challenge and risk assessment involved. Oftentimes I would face choices such as, ""Should I risk it and go in, ramming speed, to use my broadsides, or should I just stay at range and pick off fighters before moving in?"" But once you get the higher tier Destroyer and even Dreadnought class ships, all that vanished as you became a flying bullet sponge murder machine of death. Not to say that that's a bad thing at first, as it feels awesome to take down two destroyers at once, but gets boring when you realize you're unkillable.The quests mostly consist of ""Go to X location and kill Y because he's ♥♥♥♥ing up Z group."" There's some other stuff such as fetch quests, smuggling illegal goods into stations, etc, sprinkled in.There are many different weapon types, that fall into one of four categories. Even within the categories, there is a lot of variation among them.1) Turrets. Standard, ship to ship weaponry. Fires fast, reloads quickly, and does moderate damage.2) Lasers. Really fun to use, but not much variation in this type, as you can only choose between mining lasers, combat lasers, and viridian lasers. The Viridian lasers are objectively better than the combat lasers as they do higher DPS than their normal counterpart and do more damage to shields.3) Rockets. Mostly homing, super high damage weapons that can destroy fighters in one hit, and tear apart the shields or hulls of most capital ships. Only downside is they need to be replenished.4) Broadsides. The bread and butter of your ship. None of them are exactly alike, except in the fact that they're very high damaging and have no heat-up. Many vary in range, charge-up time, etc.The game has a faction reputation system going for it, but I feel it wasn't utilized well. Four of the factions (Greel, Murath, Korian, and Lightborne, plus some others I'm probably forgetting.) Are perpetually hostile and there's no way to increase reputation towards them. The remainder is the Citizenry, the Militia, and the Red Devil Cartel. Each have their own benefits for being friendly with and playing as a pirate certainly makes things interesting.Another thing I liked about this game is the events system. Occasionally, certain space stations will have different events occur in their vicinity, such as a Militia Embargo, Crime Spree, Famine, etc. The markets of this station and the surrounding ones will shift accordingly, allowing you to interact with the galaxy in a meaningful way. Other events that are not bound to space stations also occur, such as Merchants sending out distress signals, hunting down bounties, or being able to raid convoys of goods.All in all, this is a very fun game, but unless you're super into the looks of the combat and gameplay like me, I don't think the $20 price tag was quite worth it. Wait for a sale, otherwise."
76561198041396722,Recommended,290300,31712869,Posted: 12 May,all,chatsash,"I found this to be a very entertaining game with little problems here and there. The universe is (extremely unrealistically) populated with spacecraft, both friend and foe; this keeps the game engaging for a solid 20 hours before you realize that nothing new ever happens with the random encounters. You see something on the map, scan for loot, kill whatever has good loot, go off and sell it and continue on with whatever mission you're on. If you're in a slower ship, usually you just kill anything and everything. Gameplay gets a little stale once you get to million credit spacecraft since a lot of the strategy involves turtling and waiting for the enemy's shields to be depleted.But that isn't to say you can't have major fun with this, cause you can. Even though the game is mostly two dimensional (you can't really ascend or descend in your flight), you can still pull off some cool moves as you lay waste to batallions of enemy ships. The different guilds offer (a couple of) unique ships and items though it'll make minimal difference to your gameplay. I personally set up a really fast ship with ramming shields, after which I'd just hammer at enemies with short range broadsides. A lot of the unique playstyles stop working late game though, since the enemies have ridiculously tough shields. Hence the turtling as mentioned above.The storyline was nothing too special but it kept my attention.A lot of the other games of this genre and caliber are more expensive so I'd recommend to people who want to try out the whole open-universe spaceship battles genre."
