76561198013493180,Recommended,290300,24406401,"Posted: 19 July, 2016",all,Friedrich Psitalon,"Rebel Galaxy has just enough of the flair of the Firefly universe to make you smell the dust and leather of a brown coat in the distance while still being a unique and enjoyable contribution. Here's some Pros and Cons if you need them:PROS:Flexibility of playstyle - You need not be the good guy; you won't miss out on story events. (Major events happen at neutral locations, very likely an intentional decision.)Flexibility of play method - I think it'd be a bit dull to make a life of it, but if you wanted to, you could mine and haul your way to a mighty endgame vessel, rather than doing it on the backs and blood of your foes.Graphics - This isn't CCP's space-baby, but it's not a 1980s video game, either.Flavor - Unique world and reasonably unique aliens.MEH:Story Writing - It's not bad, don't get me wrong, but shocking and unusual it was not.Balance - If you take the time to get the very last ship in the game and outfit it properly, the last encounter is a silly joke. We could've used a little dynamic scaling here; the final encounters required no assistance at all, but I still got it.No Planned DLC/Expansions - I can't put this in ""CONS"" because it's a choice the devs made and that's their right; the title's short, though, and there's plenty of room for further improvement here. Really guys? You made a super popular, semi-short title with lots of room to grow, that people WANT to give you more money for, and you won't expand on it? Well. Okay, you're the designer. Meh.CONS:Game Length - If you beelined it through the game, I'd guess you could finish the main storyline in 10-12 hours. That's very short for a release, but on the other hand, it's not an expensive game.Gimmicks - There are a few gimmick strategies you can employ (not spoiling them here) that are definitely not exploits or bugs, but allow you to punch WAY outside of your weight class. (When you're smashing dreadnoughts with a frigate, that's a bit much.)"
