76561198064810938,Recommended,290300,33358603,Posted: 7 July,all,Xgrave,"Overall, I love this game. It has been forever since I've been able to play a competent, open ended space exploration title. However, I have some critiques to offer.The first critique has to do with the way the enemy AI handles encounters where they are obviously outclassed. While they do try to run when heavily damaged, when you hail them, there appears a 0% chance they will actively surrender to you when you tell them to stand down. While I can appreciate that many of these are hardened criminals you are dealing with, meaning they won't be daunted as easily as traders, their behaviour makes little sense. If someone were to obliterate a pirate's capital ship through their shields, the rest of the battlegroup ought to at least be receptive to a chance to live. It becomes rather annoying to even use the hail feature in these encounters since the automatic reply will always be something like ""sure, sure, there's no talking out of this one"". I found this broke my immersion rather than enhance it.My second critique has to do with the way saves are handled. As is, you can only save after exiting a station. This is problematic for a couple of reasons. Realistically, there is 0 reason to do this, and it just makes it tedious for longer sessions where you may have to make up for a lot of progress if you run into an unfortunate encounter. If you want to make a restriction on when players save, maybe just opt for not being able to save in combat. Further, while many save slots are on offer to the player, it seems the game uses only one at a time, with no way to access the other slots. It may be true that new games started use these slots, but personally it doesn't appear that that is the case. This critique is also problematic for another key reason. Today, shortly after purchasing my first destroyer, my game crashed. On restart, my save file was just gone... no explanation  as to why, just gone. All of my hardware in my rig is brand new, it's very unlikely that data corruption on the part of the hardware is the culprit, and now 35 hours of playtime appears to have gone down the toilet. I have to be honest, I'm quite dissapointed in this. It's not enough to make me not reccomend the game, but if it continues to occur, I might have to update my review.Finally, I have to talk about the music in the game. It's overly repetitive, it's annoying, and you are going to want to turn it off. It has it's charm for all of maybe an hour, and then grates on you. While it is worth noting that the devs have allowed for command pathing so you may add custom music, which is great, it still seems really lazy on the part of sound design.The lack of a multiplayer option is also a bit of a let down, this really keeps this game from being on the same level as titles like Elite Dangerous. Despite this, I still enjoyed the single player experience.Outside of these critiques, I found the gameplay to be fun, engaging, and simple enough to be inviting to a variety of skill sets, yet complex enough to reward players who want to dive a little deeper in terms of encounter planning, and ship functionality. Additionally, the ability to play the game the way you wish at all points without being locked into being a mercenary, trader, militia member, or pirate was truly refreshing. Numeric Scoring scales are all arbitrary, so I won't bother actually giving a score. All I will say is that if you loved older titles of this kind, like Freespace, this is the game for you. If you are a member of the uninitiated to this genre, but are still curious, I still heartily reccomend this title.Thank you for taking the time to read my review."
