76561198014404706,Recommended,290300,33391465,Posted: 8 July,all,protoKol,"This game was a fun romp is the best that i could put it.The music made this game for me, I normally think of electronic music when I play space games but the swamprock/dark country music really worked to make you feel like a small guy trying to find his way in a big scary galaxy. The combat was an arcadey style which focused around its broadside, naval combat system, which was only possible because the game was played on a single plane. The single plane is a huge downside, everythings laid out very flat and I guess this might be a good thing for people who are disoriented easily but not my cup of tea. The other major issue I had with the game was the progression system. Each system you go is progressively harder, the ships are all progressively larger. In the starter solar system the largest ships you fight are light frigates, 3 solar systems in, you're fighting some of the same sized ships from the previous system but also huge juggernauts with massive health pools. The objecitves are usually these huge juggernauts so if you want to play a light frigate youll have to skip ahead and deck yourself out with gear from 2 or 3 systems ahead. Yes thats right, even the equipment progression is forced by each solar system. All of these severley neuters the ""open world"" feel that the game was supposed to have. Combat becomes a chore, making money becomes a chore because it gets boring. This leads me to the third thing i dislike about the game, even the mining becomes a scavenger hunt. With how fast the lasers overheat, you're left getting a mediocre amount of low quality ores or scavenging belts to find 1 or 2 asteroids that contain 2 or 3 pieces of higher quality ore, gold or diamond.Pros:- An open wold feel, make money how you want (scavenging, pirating, mining, trading)- Dynamic trading economy, based on random events that occur in the stations in each system- The naval style combat- Music, the music made the atmosphere in this game, reminisent of firefly or the terran cinematics in the original starcraftCons:- Only able to travel on 1 plane (no verticle movement)- Felt too much of an arcade game- Linear progression system- Ship variety and playstyle is lacking- Fruitless miningIn all, I can recommend this game when its on sale, its a simple game in the guise of a better one. Despite strangulation by a linear progression system, the music and and unique naval style combat make it worth a try."
